2020_OUTLOOK: The current holder of the title "best baseball player on the planet" makes a compelling case for the same claim in fantasy baseball, though Trout's injury absences over the past three seasons have made that a bit debatable. He has missed 85 games, including absences due to a pair of IL stints for thumb and wrist injuries, as well as surgery to remove a neuroma from his right foot last September. However, it's not expected to delay his start to the 2020 season. All that said, Trout's performance around his absences hasn't been merely excellent -- it has been Hall of Fame good. He was baseball's leader in home runs (45), OBP (.437) and ISO (.353) at the time of his injury last year, and is the only player in baseball to hit at least 100 home runs and steal at least 50 bases while batting .300-plus in the past three seasons combined. Clearly Trout can be the best player in fantasy with more luck in the health department. That keeps him as strong a choice at No. 1 overall as anyone. It's only a debate entering 2020 because of the quality of the challengers' pool.

Yelich has flourished in his two seasons with the Brewers, and probably would be riding a back-to-back National League MVP award streak if not for the broken kneecap that prematurely ended his 2019 with 18 games left on the schedule. He had already declared himself fully healed in January, so except in the event of a spring setback, he'll be one of the top three candidates to start off your rotisserie draft, and at least top five in points-based leagues. Don't attribute all of Yelich's success to the significantly more hitting-friendly Miller Park confines as he has dramatically improved his overall hitting game since his trade from the Marlins. Most importantly, Yelich cut his ground ball rate from 56% in his final year in Miami to a career-low 43% in 2019, while also boosting his average exit velocity to a personal-best 93.1 mph. About the only potential negative we see is the possibility of more red lights on the base paths, as the Brewers recognize how important his bat is to their cause. Even that shouldn't be a dramatic drop considering his 30 steals were a career high and he has averaged 19 over the past six seasons.

The closest player to a 40/40 season in eight years -- he fell three steals shy and might have done it, if not for a left groin strain that cost him the final three regular-season games -- Acuna will be a popular choice for anyone picking first overall. He brings an appealing combination of youth/potential growth, power/speed and beneficial circumstances as the projected leadoff man for the overall seventh-best scoring offense (third in the National League) from 2019. Both Acuna's quality of contact and raw speed metrics grade among the league's elite, so he's as good a bet to deliver on the first-round investment as anyone in baseball. That said, he's not entirely without flaws. He has a lot of holes in his swing, missing on more than 30% of his cuts after the 2019 All-Star break alone, putting his batting average at risk and leading to strikeouts that eat into his points-league production. In fact, last year, he was the No. 2 player on rotisserie teams, but only No. 16 in points formats. Keep that mind if you play the latter format, but in the former, Acuna is one of the three most logical candidates to begin your draft.

A spike in his contact rate, which improved by nearly eight full percentage points -- among the largest single-year jumps this century -- fueled a 2019 National League MVP campaign for Bellinger. In the process, he became only the sixth player in history to bat at least .300 with 45-plus home runs at the age of 23 or younger, showing that he's now a complete, across-all-formats fantasy baseball first-rounder. Only one thing now stands in his path to future No. 1 overall status -- consistency. His first-half .336 batting average and .448 wOBA slipped to .263/.370 after the All-Star break. Bellinger might find that consistency, but even if he continues to exhibit ups and downs, the ups bring tops-in-the-game fantasy production and the downs are probably at worst top-50 caliber, in part because he's capable of contributing a decent handful of stolen bases.

This is what a "down" year for Betts looks like: No. 20 on the Player Rater, No. 10 in fantasy points. Struggles squaring up the ball in April and May led to a sluggish start to 2019, but the 27-year-old star batted .323/.399/.588 over his final 80 games, with fantasy production in line with his best-in-rotisserie 2016 and 2018 campaigns. In the process, he upped his line-drive rate to an astonishing (and admittedly unsustainable) 35% during that same span, resulting in the majors' third-best expected wOBA. This is proof positive that when he's right, he's capable of being the No. 1 player in any fantasy baseball format. Betts' prospective managers might be scared off by his "off year," or by his move to the more pitching-oriented NL or into a pitching-friendly ballpark in Dodger Stadium. Don't be fooled! He's an unquestionable first-round pick in every league, with a real chance at reclaiming the No. 1 hitter spot.

The 2019 season represented a slight pull-back for Lindor, who finished 29th on the Player Rater and tied for 40th in fantasy points after 12th/10th finishes in 2018. In his defense, he did that despite missing the season's first 19 games because of left ankle and right calf strains. Over the past three years, though, he has slashed .278/.342/.514 while averaging 34 home runs, 85 RBIs, 21 stolen bases and 110 runs scored, rarely straying from any of those individual numbers in any single season. Trade rumors surrounded Lindor throughout the offseason, but that might only serve to deflate his draft stock, which remains first-round caliber due to his five-tool ability. His elite defense fuels a massive number of plate appearances -- his 2,122 over the past three seasons is 50 more than anyone else -- making him one of the best return-on-investment selections that early.

Soto's career is off to a Hall of Fame-caliber start, and while his defense could still use some polish, his offense -- the part we fantasy managers care about -- only seems to be getting better. As a 20-year-old in 2019, he managed a top-10 finish in OBP (.401), OPS (.949), walks (108) and runs created (128). He concluded his year with a .276/.405/.606 slash line (with 13 home runs and 39 RBIs) in the Nationals' final 50 regular-season games before following it up with a .277/.373/.554, five-homer postseason. In the process, he boosted his average exit velocity and launch angle by significant amounts while cutting his ground ball rate from 55% to 43%, a sign that he's growing into an elite slugger at little to no expense to his batting average. Soto brings enough upside to the table to warrant first-round consideration -- and certainly so in points leagues, where his many walks strengthen his value. He's a foundation piece for dynasty/keeper leagues.

The runner-up for American League MVP honors in 2019, Bregman's batting eye is easily the sharpest in baseball. He was the MLB leader with 119 walks and had the lowest miss rate on his swings (16%). He also had an 85% contact rate that put him in the top 20. These make Bregman a sabermetric and points-league darling, where he was the highest-scoring hitter and third overall scorer. In short, he is one of the safest first-round selections in rotisserie leagues. At the same time, he enjoyed some good fortune on fly balls, with his 41 home runs being a tad unusual for his batted-ball profile. He also got fewer green lights on the base paths. Expect some pull-back in Bregman's numbers, especially in light of the Astros' involvement in the sign-stealing scandal this offseason. How wide might the impact end up? That remains unclear, but he remains a talent who shouldn't be escaping the first round.

Underrate Turner's speed at your peril. Statcast has graded him top-six in baseball in terms of sprint speed in each of his five big league seasons, something only he and Byron Buxton can claim. Only Turner has amassed 30-plus steals in the majors in each of the past four seasons. In this era of declining SB totals and homer-happy baseballs, it's the speedsters who come at a premium -- especially one like Turner who has other very fantasy-worthy skills. If you took away all of his steals, he'd have still finished among the top 140 overall players in either rotisserie or points-based leagues, and his .316/.368/.518 season-finishing slash line in 53 games showed that he might be ready to flourish with the bat as he begins the 2020 season at the age of 26. He might be a shakier second-round selection in points-based leagues because of the nature of speedsters in that scoring system, but there's no doubt he's worth the pick in a rotisserie league. In fact, he might be ready to reclaim his former status as a solid first-rounder.

Arenado has been one of the most consistent players in the game, posting a wOBA between .371-.395 and a wRC+ between 121-132 over the past five seasons. His overall wOBA since 2015 is .387, 11th best among qualified batters. The corresponding wRC+ is 127, which drops him to 34th overall. This is important since wRC+ is park neutral, giving a better idea of where Arenado might fall if he's traded out of Colorado. In fantasy terms, he's currently a late-first/early-second round player. If traded, he becomes an early-third/mid-fourth rounder, depending on the venue and quality of offense. This bakes in a small penalty in rotisserie leagues for his limited steals contribution, which is a desired commodity in today's landscape. In points leagues, Arenado's rank is better as a result of a decent walk rate and low strikeout totals.

Story is coming off back-to-back seasons with at least a .290 batting average, 30 home runs and 20 stolen bases -- the only shortstop in baseball history who can make that claim. He's seemingly a foundational fantasy piece in the format, but make no mistake that he's also a bit of a Coors Field product. He has a career road wOBA (.323) 87 points lower than at Coors (.410), and he had at least a 93-point home/road wOBA split in both of those two big years. Fortunately for Story, his two-year contract extension signed in January practically guarantees him a full 81 games at Coors yet again, but it's something daily league or head-to-head fantasy managers should keep in mind. After all, those extended road trips might be tougher to endure than those of an average player. He's still a second-round caliber talent in rotisserie, but is more of a lower-end member of the top 40 in other formats.

The 2019 season was an interesting one for Martinez. He has clearly enjoyed his time in Boston, and last season enjoyed nothing more than facing lefties, as he hit .404/.494/.887 against them in 170 plate appearances. Unfortunately for Martinez, he was barely league average against righties with a .272/.344/.449 line in 486 plate appearances against them. It was the first season in his full-time career in which Martinez had such low numbers against righties. Martinez has no peers when it comes to pulverizing lefty pitching, so a rebound against righties could lead to another huge year. He controls opt-out clauses in his contract but has a limited no-trade clause and Boston is looking to control costs. A move out of Fenway and the cozy AL East parks would be unfortunate because he is tailor-made for the park and the division.

A return to the 80%-plus contact rates he exhibited in the lower minor league levels (back in the early days of his pro career) spawned a massive breakthrough for Devers in 2019, as he obliterated his previous single-year pro bests in almost every offensive category. He showed an ability to hit both for average and power, with the only negative marks on his otherwise extraordinary campaign being the .229/.289/.405 slash line over his final 30 games and the 23.4% strikeout rate he had in September. Given that Devers at the time was a 22-year-old whose 156 games played were 12 more than he had in any previous professional season, we're willing to forgive the slump -- especially in light of his substantial skills improvements over the course of the full season. He's a player who might still have room to grow, meaning that a second consecutive year as a member of fantasy baseball's top-20 talents could yet be in the cards. Draft accordingly.

One of the most divisive players in all of baseball, Harper's first year in Philadelphia is probably unfairly regarded a disappointment in the context of the monstrous free-agent contract he signed. The truth is that he has now been a top-50 overall finisher on the Player Rater for three consecutive seasons (one of only 13 players to do so). He could well have claimed the same status in points-based leagues if he had scored only two additional points in 2017, when he finished exactly 51st. Perhaps it's not the "by far best in the game" status many predicted when he was selected first overall in the 2010 amateur draft, and Harper's .260-or-below batting averages in three of the past four seasons do leave a sour taste. Still, he has quietly become one of the more reliable sabermetrically-inclined hitters in baseball. In addition, he finished his first year for his new team slashing .277/.372/.598 with 17 home runs and a perfect 10-for-10 in steals over his final 51 games, so perhaps he's due for a boost now that he has fully adapted to his new surroundings. Harper isn't the first-round-caliber talent we had hoped for, but he's also not a player to let slip outside the top 25 picks of any draft.

There might not be a more consistent, higher-floor hitter in all of baseball right now than Freeman. In the past five seasons alone, he's the MLB leader in line-drive rate. He also finished in the top 20 in batting average, home runs, wOBA, RBs and runs scored. He's a top-eight performer among left-handed hitters in terms of wOBA against both righties and lefties. It's that stable return on investment that props Freeman up into the second round of any fantasy draft -- and arguably into a borderline first-rounder -- with the declining 1B talent pool also bolstering his value. Other than the bone spurs in his right elbow that hampered his September and required offseason surgery, Freeman comes with few questions. Considering that all offseason reports on his recovery were positive, that one seems to have a fair answer.

The Angels signed Rendon to a seven-year, $245 million contract during the offseason, dropping him into a loaded top four of their lineup that might ultimately afford him the chance to repeat 2019's career-bests of 126 RBIs and 117 runs scored. A lot of things went right for Rendon last season, but he also continued to show the kind of incremental growth he has made for the past half-decade, with his personal-best .320/.404/.592 slash rates against right-handers particularly impressive. This is a third baseman at his peak, one who finished 12th on the Player Rater and sixth overall in total points in 2019, cementing his status as a universal second-round pick. That said, there's a lengthy history of slow starts -- even if only for a couple of weeks -- when it comes to league-switching stars, so if you invest in Rendon, be patient if he adds to that historical trend.

Every year, some name-brand fantasy talent has an inexplicably catastrophic first half. In 2019, it was Ramirez. He slashed .214/.309/.325 in 80 games through June, done in by a .232 BABIP and 4.2% HR/FB rate, both of those ranking among the seven worst qualifiers. With his underlying skills still visibly intact, he rebounded in a major way thereafter, batting .321/.356/.722 with 18 homers and 53 RBIs in 49 games. A fractured right hamate cost him 26 games, but that was the only hiccup during that span. While it might be natural to assume a "meet in the middle" analysis of his polar-opposite halves, Ramirez's base skills suggest that his second half was much closer to his true self than his first, though his extreme fly-ball lean and a slight uptick in strikeouts do suggest that a return to a .300 batting average might not be in the cards. If Ramirez's prospective fantasy managers see his final stat line as a sign of decline and let him slip several rounds in your draft, scoop him up. Relative to the ADP, he's one of the stronger bounce-back candidates entering 2020.

With the move from Pittsburgh's PNC Park to Arizona's Chase Field, Marte's power bump of 2018-19, hitting 20-plus home runs in each, now seems locked in as an annual expectation. Even with the presence of the humidor, Chase represents a significant boost for him from an offensive standpoint, strengthening Marte's odds of a third consecutive 20/20 campaign -- he's currently one of only five players to hit at least 20 homers and steal at least 20 bases in each of the past two years. In fact, in a typical year, 25/25 wouldn't be out of the question, and it's possible that's undercutting his stolen-base potential. Marte might not feel like a foundational fantasy piece, but in this era of declining steals totals, his numbers warrant it: He has been a top-30 performer on the Player Rater in each of the past two years, a locked-in draft candidate in the first 2-3 rounds. In points-based leagues, though, he has finished a more modest-yet-respectable 81st and 63rd in fantasy points in those seasons, so keep in mind that he's a little less valuable there.

Baez provides a good reminder that all performance indicators need to be evaluated together. Based on plate skills, Baez appears to be a batting-average liability. However, his combination of an 84th-percentile average exit velocity and an 86th-percentile sprint speed yields a hit rate well above that usually associated with his 28% K-rate and 5% BB-rate. That said, the whiffs keep Baez's average in the .270-.290 range, so to warrant a top-20 ranking, he needs volume and stolen bases. The 27-year-old shortstop is usually durable, though he missed last September because of a hairline fracture in his thumb. That leaves steals as the key. Baez has the speed but was just 11-for-18 on stolen base attempts last season. If you're using an early draft pick on him, you're hoping new manager David Ross gives him the green light and that Baez improves his success rate. That's a risky proposition.

Last season was the second straight in which Altuve failed to answer the bell for 145-plus games. This was the norm at his peak value, having done so for six consecutive seasons. Five-category producers are great, but they have to play a lot to maximize their production, and Altuve has not played as often the past two seasons. He, like many in 2019, had his most productive power season, setting a new career high in homers, but 2019 was a down year for him in the other offensive categories. Most concerning is six consecutive seasons of decline in the running game, as his stolen-base total has fallen from 56 in the middle of the decade to just six last season. This could be his final year of five-category production, as he enters a new phase of his career.

Springer is coming off a career year in terms of rate stats, though the fantasy impact was dampened by him missing a month early on with a sore hamstring. Fueling Springer's career-high 39 homers was a new personal-best 29.5% HR/FB mark, nearly double the previous year's level. Springer's fly ball rate also ticked up for the fourth consecutive season. The main cause of the power surge was the highest average exit velocity on fly balls of Springer's career. This measurement was not influenced by the physical characteristics of the 2019 ball, so if Springer can maintain that added authority, the power gain can be maintained, unlike with a batter more reliant on the extra distance resulting from reduced air resistance. Durability is a concern, but Springer's power is approaching elite levels.

In this era of teams manipulating service time to buy additional years of control for their young, up-and-coming stars, it was refreshing to see the Mets hand Alonso their Opening Day 1B job last March, though his .352 spring batting average with four home runs surely helped his cause. Alonso rewarded the Mets with a rookie-record 53 home runs despite playing home games in a pitching-friendly ballpark. Alonso established himself as one of the game's premier power hitters. He'll be hard-pressed to follow up with as stellar a season, though, considering he became more free-swinging after the All-Star break. Perhaps that was merely the result of knowing he was in pursuit of history, but he batted just .235 with a 28.7% strikeout rate and struggled with breaking and off-speed pitches. It's common sense to expect some regression of Alonso's home run rate, but he's still capable of being a top-five fantasy first baseman and a top-40 pick overall.

Blackmon rebounded from a down season (by his standards) to bat better than .310 and slug at least .550 for the third time in four seasons. He scored 100 runs for the fourth consecutive campaign, despite playing only 140 games, his lowest total since becoming a regular in 2014. The lost time was due to an early-season calf strain, costing the veteran 14 games. Other than vanishing steals, Blackmon is displaying no signs of a skills decline. His 2019 strikeout rate was his lowest since 2016, while his average exit velocity was its highest since Statcast began collecting data in 2014. As usual, Blackmon's home splits were extreme, but barring a trade, Coors Field will be his home through at least 2021. Take the "boring guy" discount and bank one of the more stable and reliable options in the game.

The Padres made the bold decision last spring to install Tatis as their everyday shortstop beginning on Opening Day, and he rewarded them with a campaign that might've been Rookie of the Year-worthy if not for the stress reaction in his lower back that ultimately cut his season short in mid-August. It was the second such injured list stint for the young phenom; he also missed 38 days earlier in the year with a left hamstring strain, with the ailments the largest worry surrounding him entering 2020, particularly in light of his all-out style of play. Still, consider his major league rankings at the time of the back injury: ninth in batting average, slugging percentage and wOBA, and one of only five players with at least as many as his 22 home runs and 16 stolen bases. Now 21, Tatis' ceiling is potentially the sky, with plate discipline his only other likely obstacle beside health. Optimists can make a viable case for a first-round pick in a rotisserie league, or a top-25 pick in points-based, but the realist will and should wait a couple rounds longer.

A slight uptick in his launch angle fueled back-to-back career years for Bogaerts in 2018 and 2019, the latter resulting in personal bests with 52 doubles, 33 home runs and 117 RBIs. That earned him top-25 finishes on both the Player Rater and in terms of fantasy points scored, after he had been more of a top-50 performer in the three seasons that preceded it. Bogaerts' solid contact rate, line-drive stroke and placement in the heart of a productive Red Sox lineup makes him a strong bet to replicate his three-year average, even if a 2019 redux might be difficult due to its massive volume. Don't let him slip far past the first three rounds/30 picks of your draft.

Quite a few things went right for Torres in 2019: a homer-friendly home ballpark, homer-happy baseball, a professional high in plate appearances (by 53 over 2018) and 19 divisional games against the Orioles' awful pitching staff, against whom he slugged 1.045 and hit 13 of his 38 home runs. That's not to discount the performance, as he was well above average in terms of average exit velocity and Statcast's barrel rate, showed practically no platoon split, shaved nearly 4 full percentage points off his strikeout rate and did this all at age 22. Torres is only just coming into his own, and he's in fabulous circumstances to fill the pertinent fantasy categories as a member of the potent Yankees in that park. More consistency might be the final step toward becoming a true top-25-overall fantasy superstar, which is what should keep him on your draft board a round or two longer, but it's also not unthinkable he could accomplish it in 2020.

After an uneven first two seasons in the majors, both of which nevertheless concluded with good-looking final stat lines, Albies appears primed to take the next step forward in 2020. He boosted his walk rate from 5.3% to 7.7%, his Statcast average exit velocity from 86.3 to 88.8 mph and stroked 29% line drives after the All-Star break, signs that he was finally flourishing at the plate after enduring some early-career adjustments. As is, Albies finished 2019 the No. 37 name on the Player Rater and 35th in fantasy points, so he's already in the mix for a universal third-round selection even if he merely spins his wheels. Keep this in mind as you seek his upside: He made 63 of his 157 starts in the Nos. 6, 7 or 8 spots in the lineup, but he'll be in the top third this year, which should continue to boost his plate appearance and runs scored totals.

Here's a theory: Machado hasn't been as disappointing as perceived. Instead, expectations were unfairly elevated after his 2015 campaign. We saw a guy with power and speed, playing in a great park with a chance to get better. The truth is, Machado is a very good player who was aided by volume (averaging 702 plate appearances from 2015 through 2018) and Camden Yards, plus an outlier 2015 season with respect to steals. Last season's perceived dip was mostly the result of moving into a park that suppresses offense. Machado's underlying metrics were similar to previous campaigns, with a slight dip in hard-hit rate and an increase in strikeouts, both bolstering the detrimental park effects. With a year in San Diego under his belt, Machado's skills are likely to rebound, but unless the Padres pipe in humidity and bring the fences in, Petco Park will continue to hinder his production.

One of the most impactful, yet abbreviated, rookie seasons in the game's history, Alvarez's 2019 captured the rookie record for OPS (1.067) among those with at least 250 plate appearances. He joins Trevor Story as having the only two debut campaigns of at least 25 home runs in fewer than 100 games played. He's already one of the game's most feared power hitters at age 22. He managed top-15-in-baseball rates in terms of average exit velocity (92.2 mph) and barrel rate (10.3% of his trips to the plate), per Statcast data. He also got a good amount of lift on the ball and had practically no platoon split (just 15 points of wOBA). Still, the Yankees appeared to solve the Alvarez mystery in the American League Championship Series, holding him to a .045 batting average and whiffs in half his trips to the plate. While "small sample" could be the caveat, it's important to note that he batted just .152 against curveballs and had 41 of his 94 total K's against all breaking pitches. Toss in the Astros' implication in the sign-stealing scandal -- he had a 61-point wOBA home/road split -- and there are reasons to hedge your bets. Alvarez's power potential is still that of a top-50 rotisserie pick, but his K-friendly nature should keep him on draft boards far longer in points leagues.

Rizzo played through back troubles and yet was able to put up another solid year of offensive production, even though he failed to drive in 100 runs for the first time since 2014. It is a shame the back got in the way of taking advantage of 2019 baseballs, as he could have had a monster season if healthy. Rizzo hit 19 of his 27 homers before the break but spent the second half focused on hitting for average, as he raised his batting average 55 points in the second half, recognizing the physical challenges were limiting his ability to drive the ball over the fence. He is a solid four-category producer as long as the back issues are behind him, but now in his 30s, they may linger. There is no statistical worry, as he has a very high floor in both production and skills.

When the casual talk at the bar turns to batters with consistently high average exit velocity, the names Aaron Judge, Giancarlo Stanton and Miguel Sano are often bandied about. Conspicuously absent is Cruz, who belongs in the same conversation. In fact, last season the veteran slugger led all qualified hitters in exit velocity on fly balls. One of these years, taking advantage of the utility-only, old-man discount will backfire, but we're still talking about a guy averaging 41 homers over the past six seasons. Cruz's playing time has dipped for five consecutive years, but he will turn 40 in June, so some health risk comes with the territory. Bake positional flexibility into the rest of your hitters and don't hesitate to fill the utility spot with a batter deserving of being drafted much earlier or costing far more in an auction.

Where did that come from? Marte was an absolute sensation last season, and while it's easy to attribute much of his success to the rabbit baseball, grant him this: He batted .300-plus in five of the season's six months, he greatly elevated his launch angle to back the power burst with a bit of a skills bump, and he posted by far the best hard-contact rate of his career (40%). There are hints here of a reasonable chance at a semi-repeat, though "regression to the mean" does lurk, and has a bit of legitimacy considering how perfect his year felt. Marte remains a five-category contributor in rotisserie leagues, keeping him among the top 50 overall talents there, and he's not much less valuable in points-based leagues because of his high contact rate.

Shoulder problems that plagued Bryant throughout the 2018 season thankfully subsided during a bounce-back 2019, as his 31 home runs was his second-best total in any of his five big league seasons. In the process, he (mostly) restored the average exit velocity and launch angle of his better years, but due to the continued loss of some of his line-drive ability and a bit of hard contact, his batting average slipped to a career-worst .262, something that threatens to stick going forward. Bryant nevertheless remains one of the better fantasy third basemen out there, and a slightly more attractive one in points-based leagues, where his keen eye at the plate carries enough value to warrant as much as a two-round draft bump. The problem is that third base is an extremely deep position this season, so beware that he's no longer an irreplaceable commodity.

Here's a launch-angle candidate if we ever saw one. Jimenez belted 31 home runs in a better-than-you-remember-it rookie 2019, but that 48% ground ball rate is going to need some reduction if he's going to truly grow into his power -- especially this year if there's any change to the baseball. Putting that aside, Jimenez presented plenty of hints at growth entering 2020, batting .292/.328/.542 with 15 home runs in 59 games after the All-Star break, including a .340 average and nine homers in 24 games in September alone. He was long considered one of the best prospects in baseball, a prime dynasty/keeper league target, and should take another step forward as a sophomore. Don't let him sneak out of the top 50 overall picks in any fantasy redraft.

After back-to-back seasons of remarkably good health, the injury-prone version of Stanton returned in full force in 2019. The big slugger missed 141 of 162 possible Yankees games due to a pair of IL stints for left biceps and right knee sprains. A strained calf also dogged him during one of his rehab assignments and a quadriceps strain hampered him during the postseason, greatly reducing his over/under for plate appearances heading into 2020. Stanton did bat .278/.400/.486 with average exit velocity (94.2 mph) similar to his elite career norms in the 23 games (postseason included) that he did play, but that's hardly enough of a sample from which to judge. His raw strength and good eye at the plate represent a strong basis from which to regard him a top-25-overall talent in any fantasy format in each of the healthy games he plays, but how close to that status you draft him has entirely to do with how risk-averse you are.

Olson needed surgery on his hand in late March, after his team's pair of season-opening games in Japan, and that scared off a slew of prospective fantasy managers whose drafts occurred late. He bucked traditional thinking that hamate bone injuries threaten a player's power even after his recovery, as the first baseman hit 36 home runs from his May 7 return date forward, fifth most in the majors. Olson's Statcast metrics fully supported his being one of the game's premier power sources, his hard-contact rate ranking among the game's top six, and his launch angle and Barrel rates ranking among the top 25. There's every reason to believe he can maintain the performance he did during the final five months of 2019 regardless of the composition of the baseball, locking him in as a clear top-75 overall pick in all formats.

Pham had an overall productive season with Tampa Bay, but it was a slight step backward from his production in 2017 and 2018. Pham tied his career high in steals, and even improved his contact rate, but that was not reflected in his batting average. Pham went through a long spell in the summer when he had a ground ball rate over 60% because he pulled the baseball. He hit .212 on pulled ground balls last season, but expected stats say he hit those with enough quality of contact that he should have hit 40 points higher. Pham's outstanding plate discipline is why San Diego acquired him in a December deal, as the Padres were 26th in the league in on-base percentage last season. Pham should slot nicely in one of the top-two spots in the lineup and will be in position to score plenty of runs.

Injuries have become an increasing concern for Judge, who has spent at least seven weeks on the IL in both of the past two seasons, totaling 110 days lost. Between the ailments, he has remained one of the game's most fear-inducing power hitters. He has paced the majors in average exit velocity in each of his three full seasons in the majors. In those three years combined, he ranks fifth in ISO (.293) and eighth in total home runs (106) as well as HR-rate (6.5%). But don't cast Judge aside as an all-or-nothing slugger. His 267 walks from 2017-19 were seventh most in baseball, which buoyed his points-league value and fueled a sabermetrically sound .401 OBP. He was also the game's No. 12 overall performer in rotisserie and No. 16 in points-based in his record-setting, Rookie of the Year-winning campaign. Judge's stress fracture in his rib, dating back to last season, remained a big question mark at the time spring training resumed, so he's a tough pick in the early rounds without further optimism in his recovery.

Goldschmidt has played at least 155 games in six of his past seven campaigns. Last season, the health consistency was there, the run and power production were there, but the steals once again faded, and the batting average fell off with the change of home venues and divisions, as he joined the Cardinals. Goldschmidt's expected batting average, according to Statcast, was just two points higher than his actual average, but his expected slugging percentage was 55 points better than his final number. He is no longer a five-category producer, as the steals are a thing of the past, but he is an excellent three-category producer with very stable plate skills. Batting average is fluky, and a rebound there would push him back into the top 40 overall.

Hiura forced his way to the big leagues despite no obvious place to play, and by season's end had pushed Travis Shaw to the side, thanks to what was an outstanding -- and somewhat under-the-radar -- stat line. In July and August alone, during which time he started 48 of 51 Brewers games, Hiura slashed .313/.386/.604 with 11 home runs, 34 RBIs and eight stolen bases. Nevertheless, he did struggle to make contact, as his 30.7% strikeout rate was 18th worst in history among rookies with at least as many plate appearances as his 348. That'll be the area of improvement -- as well as greatest downside -- for Hiura during his sophomore season, though the power growth and speed he showed suggest he shouldn't have a hard time competing for a top-10 fantasy stat line among second basemen.

One of 2019's best breakthrough stories, Bell reworked his swing during the offseason in an attempt to add more power to his game, especially from the left side of the plate. The result was a .297/.387/.615 slash line and 28 home runs as a left-handed hitter, a near-4-degree boost to his overall launch angle and more than 2 full mph added to his average exit velocity, as well as 27 first-half home runs that earned him a place in the midsummer Home Run Derby. While some might attribute his .233/.351/.429, 10-homer second half to the "curse" that comes with that invite, Bell experienced poor fortune on batted balls and did struggle through an oblique strain. It's more likely than not that he can maintain his approach entering 2020, one that should earn him a place among the top 50 overall players in fantasy, and perhaps a round or so earlier in points-based leagues, where his patience and high contact rate are particularly valuable.

Despite his posting the first 20-homer, 40-steal season in six years in 2019, Villar was cast off by the rebuilding Orioles this winter, with their loss the Marlins' gain. They'll utilize him all over the diamond, granting him a realistic chance at in-season fantasy eligibility at third base and outfield eligibility in addition to his current second base/shortstop combo. They'll also presumably continue to grant him green lights on the base paths, exploiting his greatest strength, as he has averaged 41 steals between the majors and minors the past five seasons. Let that drive your interest in him, and in this era of declining steals, Villar's speed coupled with his double-digit homer ability makes him a viable top-50 pick in rotisserie leagues. In points leagues, as is often the case with speed-oriented players, he's a bit -- perhaps as many as 3-4 rounds -- less valuable.

For some, like Rosario, the strike zone is merely a suggestion. Last season, he swung at 46% of the pitches he saw out of the strike zone, well above the 31% league average. However, he made contact on 75% of those swings, well ahead of the 63% league mark. He's also aggressive inside the zone, though his contact there matches league norms. The result is an above-average contact rate, propping up his batting average floor. Rosario has narrowed his platoon splits, hitting southpaws for average but still deriving most of his power facing right-handers. Rosario is poor defensively, but with Nelson Cruz occupying the DH slot, Minnesota has no option but to let Rosario try to shag fly balls. He doesn't run, so there's limited upside there. Still, Rosario offers stability to a fantasy roster, providing three-category production with a non-detrimental batting average.

After stealing 79 bases over the previous two seasons combined, Merrifield was a popular choice to offer speed to a fantasy roster -- one with a solid batting average without totally sacrificing power. Unfortunately, that plan backfired as Merrifield was an inefficient 20-for-30 on the basepaths, falling well short of expectations. His sprint speed declined from the mid-90th percentile to the 86th, but that doesn't seem like enough to account for the drop. The poor success rate probably led to fewer opportunities, rendering doubt as to whether Merrifield will pick up the pace, especially since he's now 31 and likely to lose another step. Further, during new manager Mike Matheny's tenure with St. Louis, the Cardinals swiped the second-fewest bags in the league, though a good skipper should accentuate a player's strengths. While Merrifield's batted-balls skills remain intact, he should no longer be counted on to provide a bountiful foundation of steals for a fantasy roster.

Suarez made a legitimate run at the Reds' franchise record for home runs in 2019, sacrificing contact and going for an extreme fly-ball approach at the plate that resulted in 49 home runs, three shy of George Foster's 42-year-old mark. While Suarez was quite a find for his fantasy managers, his underlying metrics didn't entirely support the performance, unless he's willing to further surrender batting average in a quest to aim for the moon every swing. In short, be careful not to pay for a repeat, though he has arrived as one of the 10 best in fantasy at his position. Some spring homework: Keep tabs on Suarez's ongoing recovery from Jan. 28 shoulder surgery, as he'll probably be limited during the early stages and could be a candidate for the injured list to begin the regular season.

Meadows' 2019 was very inconsistent -- he had a pair of months with .310 or worse wOBA, and two others with .455 or better -- but the sum total of his efforts gave a lot of reason for optimism entering 2020. He nearly doubled his single-year pro best for home runs, with the metrics to fully support the boost, posted his best walk rate (9.1%) in three years with good patience metrics, and hit both righties and lefties, a crucial trait for a member of the matchup-conscious Rays. What's more, Meadows managed .294/.363/.619 slash rates with 17 home runs and 38 RBIs in his final 50 games, finishing his breakthrough campaign on a high note. If he can smooth things out, which isn't an unreasonable guess for a player entering his second full big league season, he might be able to take the next step toward a top-25 rotisserie -- and perhaps top-40 in points -- campaign.

It is tough to find players who consistently produce in fantasy baseball, but Abreu has been that guy throughout most of his career. His 2018 represented the one slip-up in his production, because it was the first time in his career that he missed time because of injury. The disappointing final numbers presented a nice buying opportunity for Abreu last spring, and he rewarded those who jumped back in on him handsomely, picking up right where he left off with his run production. The batting average is not what it was earlier in his career, but it is still above league average. Abreu is well-positioned to have another huge RBI campaign with Yoan Moncada and Tim Anderson hitting in front of him while being protected by Yasmani Grandal and Edwin Encarnacion behind him. The baseline is 30/100/.280 with room for growth.

Beware overrating Ozuna's raw numbers: His 2018 (23 homers, 3 steals) was actually the more valuable fantasy season than his 2019 (29 and 12), which shows the steep decline in home run valuations due to the rabbit baseball. His was a good-not-great campaign, with his four-year averages of 28 home runs, 94 RBIs, 4 stolen bases and a .277 batting average a better representation of his true talent. Now with the Braves on a "pillow contract," Ozuna should hit in the heart of another productive lineup, with an underrated top three slotted ahead of him to support his quest at another 90-plus RBIs. He's well worth a pick in the early-to-middle rounds of any fantasy draft.

Few players can boast the kind of overall improvement to their game the past two seasons as Semien. Formerly a defensive liability with modest pop, he has become one of the better shortstops with the glove, and he posted a professional-best 84.5% contact rate in 2019. Semien saw his fantasy point total soar by 205, earning him a spot in the top 10 overall, and he finished 91 spots higher on the Player Rater as well. He finished the season on quite a high note, slashing .313/.398/.645 with 16 home runs in his final 52 games, and while there's a likelihood of some regression in his numbers, his skills bumps shouldn't be discarded outright. Regard Semien as a top-10 fantasy shortstop in all formats, with the chance he could finish among the top five in points leagues.

Robles' rookie season was a solid one -- top 100, at that -- in rotisserie leagues, but it wasn't without flaws. He generated a surprisingly low rate of hard contact (rating among the bottom 5% in the majors), posted the worst walk (5.7%) and strikeout rates (22.7%) of his professional career and hit only three homers in his final 60 games (backed by a near-50% ground ball rate). Those trends limit his points-league upside, making him more of a mid-round than a top-100 pick. Fortunately, Robles is young enough to improve, turning only 23 in May, and he did show a hint of pop in the early stages of 2019, not to mention he was a plus defender who should earn a maximum amount of playing time. Since he's a speedster, don't let him slip too far in your roto draft.

Chapman continues to show growth at the plate, and considering he's one of the game's premier defenders, he'll continue to get a maximum number of plate appearances to drive his numbers home. For the second consecutive year, he improved his overall contact rate and ranked in the top-20 qualifiers in baseball in terms of hard contact rate, supporting his home run spike while suggesting that his .249 batting average might've been misleading. Chapman's skills have quietly become elite in points-based leagues, as he's a potential top-40 overall pick there after finishing among the top 60 in that format in 2019. He's also a highly attractive pick in rotisserie leagues, though, and should be drafted among the top 10 at his position.

Castellanos' finish to 2019, following his trade to the Cubs, was a thing to behold: He batted .321/.356/.646 with 16 home runs (tied for ninth most) and 43 runs scored (tied for fifth), finally tapping into the elite batting average and power combinations fantasy managers had been anticipating for years. Now with the Reds, he's moving to yet another favorable environment in which to hit, for an offense that should be significantly improved upon 2019's bottom-10 unit. The smart money, though, has Castellanos regressing off his hot finish, probably closer to his three-year averages of a .287 batting average and 25 home runs. He should be able to turn in those totals, ones worthy of a top-25 fantasy outfielder at the very least, and probably warrants a pick slightly sooner than that due to his recent signs of growth. One note: He came within nine doubles of the single-season record, something that had a lot more value in points-based leagues than you might think, as he finished 31 spots better in that format than in rotisserie leagues. Castellanos' extra-base hit ability is especially attractive in points leagues.

Mondesi's game is one of extremes. He had the majors' second-most stolen bases (43) despite appearing in only 102 games but also the second-highest swinging strike rate (22%). A separated shoulder that resulted from a diving play in mid-July and required offseason surgery ruined what was an otherwise productive campaign from a rotisserie perspective, and it underscored how much variance is involved in his game. A fully healthy Mondesi is capable of 60-plus steals -- that alone propelling him into the top 25 in rotisserie formats -- with double-digit power, albeit with a so-so batting average. However, his free-swinging nature leaves him susceptible to slumps, and he does have a troubling injury history at a young age. Mondesi's potential makes him well worth selection within the first 100 picks of your rotisserie draft, but he's not someone to reach for -- and in points-based leagues, he's someone better left to the late rounds because of his questionable approach at the plate.

"Three true outcomes" hitter: Thy name is Joey Gallo. No player in baseball history has seen a greater percentage of his plate appearances end in a home run, walk or strikeout than Gallo (59%). But while he's an all-or-nothing type, his flaws aren't nearly as damaging as many of the models who have come before him. While Gallo's 2019 season ended July 23 due to a broken hamate bone, until that point he had boosted his line-drive rate to 25% and posted top-six Statcast numbers with his 93.0 mph average exit velocity, 52.3% hard-contact rate and 11.4% barrel rate per trip to the plate, things that make him the most truly threatening power source in all of baseball. When healthy, Gallo stakes a legitimate claim to a 50-homer, 100-walk, albeit 200-strikeout, ceiling season, and his improving metrics make him less of a drain on your batting average than once feared. Check back on him during spring training to ensure no lingering injury effects, but if he's in the clear, he's a potential points-league monster (top 25-capable) who should also find himself in the season-ending Player Rater top 50.

The arrow was pointing up for Schwarber as 2019 concluded, and as he enters his age-27 season, he might be primed for his best season yet. Last season, for the first time, he handled left-handed pitching adequately, hitting .229/.306/.450 against southpaws, with his continued improvement against them culminating in a .280/.366/.631 slash line and 20 home runs in 70 second-half games. The Cubs saw this and granted him career highs with 155 games and 610 plate appearances, with those rising numbers making him a much stronger selection than previously in weekly formats. Schwarber is now a locked-in top-100 asset in points-based leagues, and he has a realistic chance at reaching that tier in rotisserie leagues, too, especially with the new designated hitter role giving him a soft landing spot in the Cubs' everyday lineup.

If you're a believer in a player requiring some time to adapt to new surroundings, surely you'll be tantalized by the second half of Realmuto's first Phillies season: .278/.327/.565 rates, 15 home runs, 41 RBIs, 5-for-5 on stolen bases and 37 runs scored in 60 games (out of the team's 71). His full season was scattered with positives, including personal bests in runs (92), doubles (36), homers (25), RBIs (83), total bases (265) and walks (41). Realmuto was tops at his position on the Player Rater and finished four points shy of the positional lead in the latter format, supporting his case to be the unanimous No. 1 catcher off any draft board again in 2020. He brings a rare five-category combination for a backstop, as well as the durability points-league managers desire. The main question is whether it's worth paying a premium to net the best overall catcher. It's probably worth it after the first 50 picks or so in a two-catcher league but closer to 75th in ESPN's one-catcher standard format.

As Correa enters his age-25 season, his plate appearance totals have shown an alarming pattern, going from 660 to 481 to 468 to a career-worst 321 in 2019, the latter the product of a fractured rib and back discomfort that cost him a combined 86 days' action. The back issues are especially disturbing, since they also plagued him in 2018 and have at times cut into his power output. Correa did hit eight home runs while slugging .575 in 22 games between injured list stints, showing that his bat still has some thump, but he also batted .238 during that time as he seemed to trade some contact for power. A healthy, strong spring would go a long way toward restoring Correa's status as a clear top-10 fantasy shortstop, as right now treating him as that is more of a throwback to his overwhelming scouting reports than his recent results.

Departing Coors Field turned out to be not as damning for LeMahieu's fantasy value as expected, and in fact, he was often hailed as a top contender for MVP until deep in the 2019 season. Some of that was the sudden power boost; he hit a career-high 26 homers, in a season when everyone was doing so, inflated by a 13th-ranked 17.0% home run/fly ball percentage, with 19 of those coming at Yankee Stadium. Expected regression explains how he's more of a borderline top-100 fantasy asset entering 2020 than a repeat candidate, though he's one of the stronger return-on-investment players among that group, thanks to his being locked in as the Yankees' everyday second baseman and leadoff hitter this time around. He's also every bit as attractive a pick in points leagues as roto, so draft him with confidence, even if he sees his homers revert to 2018's 15.

Last season was the "perfect storm" for Soler. The rebuilding Royals had an open DH spot for the defensively challenged former Cub, and they didn't care about his proclivity for striking out. The rest was up to him -- and Soler came through, lofting the ball more than he had in 2018 and hitting it harder than at any time in his career. Not only did Soler revert to a 41% fly ball rate, but he lowered his infield pops by 5 percentage points -- a significant amount for someone with a 26% K rate. After all, an infield fly, like a whiff, is a guaranteed unproductive out. Soler played 56 games in the outfield last season, but could be hard-pressed to get the minimum required to avoid DH-only eligibility in future seasons. Even so, in today's homer-happy landscape, Soler has finally broken through and looks to be a quality source of power for the next few years.

A broken left hand suffered when he was hit by a pitch in Triple-A in April delayed Bichette's ascent to the majors in 2019, but once he arrived, he was every bit as good as advertised. His 29 extra-base hits from his July 29 debut forward ranked among the majors' top 15, and his 112 total bases ranked among the top 30. In fact, he became the first player in the modern era to double in nine consecutive games, something that should particularly appeal to those of you in points-based leagues. Bichette contributes solid totals in all five rotisserie categories, and considering he hit for more contact and stole more bases in the minors than he showed in Toronto, it's possible he'll take the next step forward and become a locked-in top-10 shortstop in 2020. He's a great dynasty building block and has the requisite upside to warrant a pick within the top 100, even in redraft formats.

For the second consecutive season, Conforto boosted his home run total, but perhaps most importantly, he stayed healthy for long enough to appear in more than 150 games. As he has entered his prime, he has also incrementally improved his contact rate while showing the same level of elite plate discipline he has had throughout his big league career, hinting that the best might be yet to come. Conforto should again serve a middle-of-the-lineup slugger for the Mets, a top-25 fantasy outfielder in rotisserie leagues who could be nearly a top-50 overall asset in points leagues.

In the two seasons since Hoskins hit the scene, bashing 18 homers in just 50 games, he has increased his average launch angle while hitting the ball with less authority and fanning more. The added loft and reduced average exit velocity not only curtailed Hoskins' home run production, but his hit rate on fly balls staying in the yard is now just 11%. Factor in that Citizens Bank Park increases foul outs by 64% (Hoskins had 20 last season), and a career-low .226 batting average makes sense. As such, Hoskins is one of the rare hitters who should be trying to reduce his average launch angle. Despite declining average and waning power, Hoskins has maintained an exceptional walk rate and thus remains an asset in points leagues and OBP formats. He's less appealing in batting-average leagues, but there's upside in the event he reverts to 2017's swing mechanics.

In contrast to the lofty expectations surrounding him entering 2019, Guerrero's rookie campaign cannot be termed anything short of a disappointment. The No. 73 player selected overall in ESPN leagues in the preseason, Guerrero finished only 325th on the Player Rater, though his contact-oriented swing and extra-base ability helped him earn the 203rd spot in terms of fantasy points, a format that seems to favor his skill set. Knee issues seemed to hamper his power potential, and he struggled mightily in the field, things that'll need to improve if he's to reach his future-MVP ceiling. Guerrero did spend this past winter working on his conditioning, a promising sign for a player who has sometimes drawn criticism for a lack of it, and he'll be one to watch for indicators of improvement during spring training. He remains one of the most attractive dynasty-league building blocks and has enough raw talent to warrant selection amongst the top 100 in any redraft format.

It was always difficult to imagine the Dodgers moving Muncy to a reserve role, taking a 134 wRC+ bat out of the lineup on a regular basis. That remote possibility is now a highly unlikely proposition after Muncy signed a three-year, $24.5 million extension in February. He should see the bulk of his action at first base with Gavin Lux earmarked for second. Muncy fell back some from 2018, but that was inevitable. Still, under the hood, Muncy's supporting stats were similar to 2018, so he's established a high floor, albeit with a tempered batting average due to below-average contact. Power is his game as Muncy's high average exit velocity on fly balls and a penchant for lofting contact work in concert. Points- and OBP-league participants take note, as Muncy's high walk rate is ideal for those formats.

Ohtani will be nearly 22 months removed from Tommy John surgery at the time of 2020 Opening Day, so there's a good chance we'll see him on the mound a significant amount this season. He has already flashed elite ability on both sides of the ball, going 5-for-9 in quality starts with a 3.10 ERA and 30.5% strikeout rate before injuries began to surface in 2018, and hitting .287/.357/.596 with 15 home runs in 59 games as a near-regular designated hitter during the second half of 2019. In leagues with daily lineup locks, the ability to maximize his contributions as either hitter or pitcher, depending upon his daily role, boosts his value ahead of weekly leagues, where he'll be locked into one role or another for the entire scoring period. He's capable of a top-100 contribution overall in any format, even if he's limited to only one role or the other, but the case can be made he's a top-50 talent in our game thanks to the daily format.

The Bringer of Rain signed a four-year deal to move north to Minnesota and become the Bringer of Sleet. Donaldson joins a very potent Twins lineup and will not have the pressure of coming in and carrying a huge load as many free agents often do. Donaldson simply makes an already-strong lineup even better and will be well-insulated hitting between Nelson Cruz and Eddie Rosario, assuming Cruz is fully recovered from his wrist injury. Otherwise, Donaldson moves up a spot in the order. Donaldson has just once driven in more than 100 runs in a full season, but that should not be a problem this season in Minnesota. A run at MVP-caliber numbers could be in store for him in 2020. This was the perfect landing spot for his 2020 fantasy futures.

Laureano has earned his status as a good all-around player, but can he yet be considered great? While he's most highly regarded for his defense, his metrics weren't eye-popping, and while he did fill five rotisserie categories, they came with a disappointing 5.6% walk rate that threatens his ability to repeat his .288 batting average. Injuries held Laureano back for parts of 2019, but his .358/.411/.679 September rates gave a strong recent impression, which is why he'll be a universally regarded top-100 overall fantasy pick entering 2020. Expect regular at-bats as the Athletics' center fielder, with another season of solid, if unspectacular, across-the-board numbers.

We'll get it out of the way first: Moncada's .406 BABIP was the second highest by any qualified hitter since World War II, and that explains how he was able to bat 80-plus points higher than he did in any of his previous three big league seasons. Still, while regression is inevitable for Moncada in the batting average category, he has room for growth. He went on a .353/.393/.583 tear in 35 season-concluding games after recovering from a hamstring injury, including showing more contact in September, and he was more efficient on the basepaths. Moncada is a better pick in rotisserie leagues than in points-based formats, where his somewhat free-swinging nature detracts from his value. He's nevertheless worth a pick in the first 10 rounds in the former and only a round or two later in the latter.

Many fantasy managers expected a breakthrough from Benintendi in 2019; what they received was a season that barely cracked the top 200 overall in rotisserie and fell just shy of the top 300 in points-based formats. A professional-worst 22.8% strikeout rate had a lot to do with it, and he seemed to struggle to get any sort of elevation on the ball at all in his final 30 games, batting .175/.268/.268. Fortunately, Benintendi is still 25 years old with plenty of time to turn his career around, and that he continued to show no discernible platoon split -- he actually had a wOBA 15 points better against lefties than righties -- was promising. He can still fill five rotisserie categories and has a good enough historical reputation for contact to be equally attractive in points leagues, but it'd help if he had a solid spring before we invest at anything more than the price of a top-25 outfielder.

Moustakas finally got the multiyear deal he deserved in each of the prior two offseasons. He is coming off a three-year cycle of consistent production while playing for both Kansas City and Milwaukee. He added more loft to the baseball in recent seasons, and the results have paid off for his run-production totals. "Moose" had issues earlier in his career with lefties but has done better against them in recent seasons and had his best season yet against southpaws last year. In fact, he was more effective against them than he was righties in 2019. He carries the added bonus of being eligible at second base and third base on draft day, and the move to Cincinnati's ballpark keeps him in a friendly environment for his hitting style. Expect more of the same from Moustakas in 2020.

McNeil underwent surgery to repair a broken bone in his right wrist in early October but is expected to make a complete recovery in time for the spring. His 2019 performance caught some off guard. A strong batting average wasn't at all that surprising, but the power spike was an eye-opener. A significant uptick in hard-hit rate and average exit velocity without sacrificing much contact did the trick. McNeil hit fewer fly balls, which hindered the jump, though the extra grounders aided his average. That's a tradeoff he'll take, even in this power-hungry environment. McNeil's average fly ball distance was short relative to other 20-plus-HR hitters. Add in the chance that the 2020 ball doesn't travel as far and McNeil is a strong candidate to give back much of his power gain. However, his high contact rate offers a bankable floor. His multipositional eligibility doesn't hurt, either.

Reyes has elite raw power and showed off his pop with 36 home runs in his first full major league season, split between San Diego and Cleveland. He is not a good defender, and that played a significant part in the Padres trading him to an American League team at the deadline. With the Indians, Reyes' strikeout rate jumped to 32.5% and his rate-power numbers declined, but he was still 9% better than the average MLB hitter in terms of wRC+ when all was said and done. He provided one of the first "best shape of his life" stories in 2020, reportedly shaving 18 pounds over the offseason, and there's some talk that he could play more outfield than originally expected. That's good news for his 2021 positional eligibility in fantasy leagues, but he's still likely a DH long term. He projects to hit fifth in Cleveland's batting order this season.

Here's how great Sanchez's power was in 2019. He matched his professional best with 34 home runs, yet he did so in 92 fewer trips to the plate. Unfortunately, injuries have become a persistent problem for him, as he has now made five separate trips to the IL in the past three seasons alone -- for biceps, groin (three times) and calf issues. If you're feeling lucky, Sanchez could stay on the field long enough to easily lap the catcher category in home runs, and one would presume from his past history of better contact rates that he'd improve enough there to raise his batting average from last year's .232. He's well worth the early pick because of the dearth of quality catchers, but don't get so carried away with your expectations that he's one of your first few players off the board.

Now devoid of shoulder woes, Brantley eclipsed the .300 plateau for the second straight season. However, he took an odd pathway to get there. As is the case with most batters, Brantley's home splits were better than on the road. However, his road splits were a career best, while his home performance was down a bit. If he doesn't improve on his home numbers and reverts to historical road levels, Brantley's average could dip. This is especially important since he is a compiler, relying on volume and a high average to bully up runs and RBIs. Additionally, age and injuries have sapped Brantley of his double-digits steals expectation. His floor is still one of the highest in the league, but reaching for Brantley in fantasy to stabilize batting average could be detrimental. Good thing he often comes at a "boring, aging guy" discount.

Barring a disastrous spring, Robert, one of the game's top prospects, should find himself in the Opening Day lineup for the White Sox, after the team signed him to a multiyear contract and promoted him to the 40-man roster on Jan. 2. That decision made him one of the safest rookie investments in years, locking in his playing-time prospects in a way we rarely see in this era of service-time manipulation. Robert will need it. He's a free swinger who might need time to adapt to the game's most competitive level, having posted combined 5.1% walk and 74.5% contact rates between Double- and Triple-A. Still, he's a potential five-category fantasy standout, having hit .328/.376/.624 with 32 HRs and 36 stolen bases across three minor league levels in 2019. Expect inconsistency from him initially, but he's well worth selecting as a Nos. 4-5 mixed-league OF in redraft leagues and as a building block in dynasty formats.

Aaron Judge, Joey Gallo or Sano -- take your pick. They don't hit the ball -- they punish it! They also fan a ton, the latter two in particular. The key with Sano is health and conditioning. Looking at his 2019 campaign, there are reasons for optimism. He had surgery for a mysterious lacerated ankle, finally taking the field in mid-May. While he missed time now and again, Sano avoided another visit to the IL. The move across the diamond to a less physically demanding 1B position should benefit him. While Sano's career 36% K-rate might be a detriment in standard rotisserie leagues, a 12% career BB rate mitigates the damage in OBP leagues, as well as in points formats lacking an excessive penalty for strikeouts. Power can be found later in drafts, but not with the level of runs and RBIs that Sano can also provide.

Anderson's 2019 was a brilliant mix of skills improvement and exceptional fortune, with a key takeaway being the fact that he was one of only seven players (and two middle infielders) to manage 15-plus HR and 15-plus SB for a third consecutive season. Skills-wise, his 78.7% contact rate represented a professional best and he began to show a bit more lift on the ball, but he also benefited from an unsustainable .399 BABIP while walking a miserable 2.9% of the time. These rates threaten to regress and may result in as much as a 75-point drop in his 2020 batting average. Anderson isn't actually the top-50 rotisserie performer he appeared to be, but he contributes enough in the five prominent categories to warrant a midround/top-12-SS pick there. The problem is in points leagues where he's significantly less valuable because of his poor plate discipline.

Kepler credited the juiced ball for his personal HR surge, but he should give himself a fair amount of credit as well. It's like there were tons of players who hit 36 homers last season after previously managing no more than 20. The outfielder's .252/.336/.519 slash line represented career bests in all three categories, while his 98 runs and 90 RBI were also easily career highs. Statcast generally supported his breakout, as it was driven by more career-bests in barrel rate, exit velocity, launch angle and hard-hit rate, even if his .458 xSLG suggests he overachieved by a fair amount. He has room to regress and still be a productive bat.

Seager's first year back after Tommy John surgery wasn't eye-popping, but rather a serviceable effort that will probably leave prospective fantasy managers wondering whether he's capable of more. While he displayed a good share of contact as he raised his launch angle to a career-high 14.1 degrees, he also saw a dip in hard contact, had a 59 point wOBA platoon split and missed time with a hamstring injury. Fortunately, Seager's strong finish offers some hope of his taking the next step in 2020, as he hit .288/.317/.588 with 10 home runs and 40 RBIs in his final 40 games. He'll enter the year as the Dodgers' starting shortstop, and isn't far off a top-10 valuation in fantasy at his position.

Mercado began the 2019 season with Triple-A Columbus, slashing .294/.396/.496 before getting the call to report to the big club in mid-May. The 2013 second-round draft pick of the Cardinals registered a fine rookie season, finishing with 15 homers and the same number of steals. Long term, Mercado projects more as a stolen-base threat than a home run guy, sporting 97th percentile sprint speed. Mercado's average fly ball distance is relatively short, but most of his homers are down the line. With only one year under his belt, it's unclear if this pull nature will continue, allowing Mercado to perennially threaten double-digit homers. Truth be told, he'd be better off with the Willie Mays Hayes approach, keeping the ball on the ground while regaining the plate discipline displayed in the minors. Draft Mercado for steals and consider home runs a bonus.

On the one hand, Dahl set career highs in games played and plate appearances. On the other, it was still only 100 games and 413 plate appearances. He reinforced previous buzz with an .877 OPS. The thing is, while everyone benefits from Coors Field, Statcast data suggests Dahl is helped more than most: His average exit velocity and launch angle wouldn't typically translate into his production. This is corroborated by home/away splits, as he had a .412 wOBA at home compared to just .308 on the road. Over the years, Dahl has missed action from rib, back, hamstring and abdominal issues, as well as a stomach virus, a broken foot and a sprained ankle costing him the final two months of the 2019 campaign. The best use of Dahl is to stream his home at-bats in leagues with ample reserves. Save an IL spot for him.

Buxton's past 162 big league games played have amounted to a .260 batting average, 21 home runs, 29 stolen bases (in 32 attempts) and a .224 ISO. That's the good news. However, he has also made six IL trips and missed 120 Twins games during the same amount of time, due to migraines, toe, wrist, concussion and shoulder (twice) issues. That's less appealing. Buxton is as injury-prone as they come, and while his top-shelf speed and defense coupled with a hint of pop has value, it's difficult to ignore his fragility as he enters his age-26 season with a decreasing long-term ceiling. He's a No. 4-5 OF in mixed rotisserie leagues, and one with whom to brace for headaches. He might not be worth the chance at all in points-based leagues, where his free-swinging ways are an additional problem.

Every season, a handful of players surprise us with career years out of nowhere; Escobar was in that group in 2019. The expected stats suggested that Escobar overachieved in 2018, which left many skeptical of what he would do in 2019. He silenced his critics and then some with a career season, but the expected stats once again suggest pessimism of a repeat, indicating that Escobar overachieved in batting average and slugging percentage. Back-to-back seasons of 600-plus plate appearances is nice, and he has made the most of the playing time to compile some solid-to-awesome production. The running game is the only area where he is not helping you, but he provides enough run production that you'll forgive him for not running. There is nothing special in his indicators, but it's tough to argue with his work the past two seasons.

Eaton was a wonderful table-setter for the world champions, using his plate discipline and ability to get on base to have a career-best season. "Spanky" has long had the on-base chops, but he missed significant time in 2017 and 2018 with major injuries. Last season was the perfect storm, as he had the most playing time in four seasons, hit first or second in a potent lineup nearly all season and set career highs in home runs and runs scored. We saw him do this in back-to-back seasons with the White Sox in 2015 and 2016, so 2019 looks more like him reestablishing his abilities rather than a new level of performance. The key now is for him to avoid a major injury and put together two seasons of health. The RBIs may never be there, but the rest of the production is solid.

Initially destined to be a utility infielder with an empty batting average, Gurriel has matured into a slugger with a bat worthy of left field. Well, that's what the Blue Jays hope anyway after the 26-year-old Cuban blasted 20 homers in what amounts to a little over half a season of full-time play last year. An April trip to Triple-A along with wrist, knee and quad woes cut into Gurriel's playing time before he missed the last week of the season due to an appendectomy. Gurriel's power blossomed after he increased his average launch angle by four degrees, taking better advantage of his 71st-percentile average exit velocity. While the future looks bright for the younger of the Gurriels, durability and the chance he might give back some of his skills gains are both concerns. Risk notwithstanding, hitting in the upper portion of an improving lineup is inviting.

Biggio's rookie year was surprisingly productive in all fantasy formats, but to be clear, the appeal of drafting him in 2020 is his elevated statistical floor. That's the product of his elite walk rate and a perfect 14-for-14 performance stealing bases for the Blue Jays last season, greatly increasing his chances for more green lights. He struck out a lot -- 28.6% of plate appearances -- and had a 20.1 degree launch angle that was sixth highest in the majors, so batting average might become a real problem as he fully adapts to the big leagues. There's a lot to like in Biggio's game, but for now he's more of a high-upside, borderline top-10 option among second basemen than something greater.

It was quite the homecoming for Santana in Cleveland, as he tied a career high with 34 homers while setting career highs in both RBIs and runs scored. The 110 runs was a shocker that overshot every projection -- we just do not see that type of runs total from a player who spends his time hitting third or fourth in the batting order. Santana, Freddie Freeman and Anthony Rendon were the only players to score at least 110 runs while hitting third or fourth last season, while Jose Ramirez and Miguel Cabrera are the only other players in the past decade to do so. Santana's full-season career-best .397 OBP gave him plenty of run-scoring opportunities in a talented lineup. The conditions are there for him to have another huge season, but look for some of those runs to move to the RBI category.

Injuries ruined Davis' 2019, as a hip issue (from when he ran into an outfield wall on May 8) ultimately cost him eight games on the IL. Then, a hand injury resulting from his being hit by a pitch on June 27 cost him an additional three games, after which point he slashed just .189/.273/.304 with a 27.7% strikeout rate in 65 games. Before those ailments, especially in the season's first three weeks when he batted .270/.316/.689 in 19 games, Davis seemed to be the same slugger he had been in the three prior seasons. As such, it's not outrageous to expect a rebound should he report to spring training fully rested and healed. That version is a top-50-overall fantasy performer across all formats, even as a DH-only player. Keep close tabs on his progress during spring training. Since the prospect of further injuries will (and should) deflate his draft stock into the middle rounds, he might be quite the profit center.

Lux forced his way into the Dodgers' September and postseason plans thanks to .347/.421/.607 rates, 26 HRs and 10 SBs in 113 games combined between Double-A Tulsa and Triple-A Oklahoma City, flashing enough pop in the process to put himself in the mix at 2B entering spring training. While that will be a battle, his blue-chip prospect status might earn him an edge, assuming the Dodgers don't want to keep his service time in check. Make no mistake, Lux can rake. He's the kind of player with easy top-10 potential at second base if he's in an everyday role, but his base stealing comes with some questions, as he was only 52-for-77 during his minor league career. He's a top dynasty/keeper-league prospect, and one who could settle in the top 100 in redraft leagues if he's looking good during spring training.

One of only four players in 2019 to have a 30/30 season between the majors and minors combined, Tucker enters spring training in the mix for a starting OF spot with the Astros. To make the team -- and to ultimately succeed once he does -- he'll need to cut down on the strikeouts (20 in 67 big league at-bats) and show greater patience, lest he become a streaky performer, especially in batting average. Tucker's minor league track record and his 23 years of age provide him plenty of room for growth, and his 76-of-95 SB success rate over the past three seasons elevates his floor in that category. If his spring progresses well, he'd be worth a top-30 fantasy OF draft selection in all formats, but even if it appears he's minor league-bound initially, he's worth a late-round stash. Be forewarned, however, that continued swing-and-misses would extend his downside in points leagues.

Gurriel was one of the many players who took to the new baseball nicely, hitting as many homers in 2019 as he had the previous two seasons combined. Gurriel added more loft last year, hitting more flyballs than groundballs for the first time in his career. Nineteen of his 31 homers came at home, and his batting average at Minute Maid Park was 24 points higher than it was on the road. Before you read too far into that, know that was the reverse of the previous two seasons, when he hit for a higher average on the road. Gurriel is at his best with runners on base; he has a career .739 OPS with the bases empty, an .888 OPS with anyone on base and a .962 OPS with runners in scoring position. The Houston lineup presents many opportunities for him to continue that trend.

Incremental growth in his contact rate in both of his two full big league seasons has helped Rosario elevate his game to that of a top-15 rotisserie and top-20 points-based shortstop. That's saying something considering he comes with defensive questions and is only 50-for-74 attempting steals in his big-league career.
