At 24, he's still young enough to continue to improve, but it's unclear whether his total package includes ceilings greater than a .290 batting average, 20 home runs or 20 stolen bases. His categorical balance makes him an upside play from amongst the middle-infield tier in rotisserie formats, but he's a more dangerous selection in points leagues due to his free-swinging nature.

Turner hit the ball hard with loft for a third consecutive season and exceeded 20 homers for the third time in four years. He also failed to play more than 135 games for the third consecutive season, as he has not been able to avoid the injured list. When he is on the field, the production has been very consistent, even if his strikeout rate has worsened year over year in that time. His 16% strikeout rate in 2019 was still much better than league average, but that rate was 10% two seasons ago. Now in his mid-30s, Turner faces the possibility of his bat beginning to slow down in addition to the health questions. His production could dip if the quality of contact starts the slide in 2020 that his contact rate has seen the past few years.

Grandal ended up in one of the best possible landing spots for a free agent this winter. He will hit in the middle of a potent lineup, insulated by Jose Abreu and either Edwin Encarnacion or Eloy Jimenez. Grandal should be able to use his plate-discipline skills and the home park to his advantage and challenge the 30-homer plateau again while setting career highs in both runs and runs driven in. He has been an above-average run producer in each of the past four seasons while getting nearly all of his playing time at catcher due to his framing skills. That will likely continue unless Abreu needs to cover the DH role due to an Encarnacion injury. He should be an outstanding contributor at catcher for the run-production categories while hitting for just enough average.

One of these years, Encarnacion is going to show his age and see his statistical production fall off. He has hit 30 or more homers in eight consecutive seasons and moves to a ballpark that has favorable conditions for him to make it a ninth consecutive season. He has missed time in each of the past two seasons with arm injuries but has still managed to put up his numbers while playing in strong lineups. The move to the south side of Chicago presents him with another potent lineup in which to drive in runs. The Statcast data shows that his outcomes profile continues to stay one step ahead of his age, so we should get another year of 30 homers -- or 10-12, when prorated to 60 games -- from him. His health will determine what else he brings to the table in 2020.

The Dodgers have limited Pederson's exposure to lefties, giving him just over 100 PA vs. LHP from 2018-19. While that capped his counting-stat production, it helped Pederson reach a new level with his ratios and rate stats. He went from being league average by wRC+ in 2017 to 26-27% better than league average the past two seasons, while setting new career highs in BA in back-to-back years. After posting K-rates in the high-20s in his first three years in the league, Pederson sat around 20% in recent seasons. The soon-to-be 28-year-old has gained dual eligibility, having played 20 games at first base in addition to 122 in his customary outfield spot. A February trade to the Angels fell through and the Dodgers are saying Pederson will be part of the team in 2020 after all, so don't expect an increase in playing time. For fantasy players, Pederson is better off in a platoon role anyway.

In an era when most players are running less, Andrus swiped 31 bags last season, his first with 30 since he notched 42 in 2013. The Rangers led MLB in pilfers under first-year skipper Chris Woodward, and with Texas moving to a less hitter-friendly ballpark, Andrus should continue to get the green light. That said, the 31-year-old's sprint speed is just 46th percentile, so counting on a full repeat is risky. In addition, despite a rebound in batting average, Andrus' on-base skills are in question after he posted the lowest walk rate of his career last season. In Andrus' favor is volume. He's played at least 145 games in 10 of his 11 seasons. A consistently high contact rate gives Andrus a stable batting-average floor, and he has the ability to compile double-digit homers. Just be skeptical of another 30-steal campaign.

It wasn't long ago that a rookie producing .314/.377/.503 in 134 games (like Reynolds did in 2019) would make him a unanimous choice for Rookie of the Year hardware. Amazingly, he finished a distant fourth in the NL voting. After posting a 1.181 OPS to open the season with Triple-A Albuquerque, Reynolds was summoned by the Pirates as an injury fill-in and ended up staying in the Steel City all year. While Reynolds' Statcast metrics suggest he will avoid a dramatic sophomore slump, regression is likely, as he outperformed both his expected batting average and slugging percentage. A 67th-percentile hard-hit rate and 76th-percentile sprint speed support an above-average BABIP, leaving a solid floor. Reynolds hit second in the order for most of last season, but he could drop down with a return to health of some teammates. That said, Reynolds should still hit high enough in the lineup to be productive, providing batting average support to fantasy teams.

Blocked at every field position entering last spring after a disappointing 2018 rookie campaign, Kingery emerged as a super-utility player, his hot start with the bat ultimately earning him 109 starts in the Phillies' final 117 games across five positions. He'll presumably settle in at third base to begin 2020, but he also carries outfield eligibility and could factor into the second-base or shortstop mixes if injuries dictate. Kingery's free-swinging ways are a tad more problematic in points-based leagues, but his 15-for-19 SB rate in 2019, his fly ball leanings and an over-8% rise in hard-contact rate all make him an attractive late-round pick in mixed rotisserie leagues.

Cain saw action in 148 games last season, but his numbers at the plate and on the basepaths took a major dip. After one of the best hitting seasons of his career in 2018, Cain had his worst OPS since 2013 and stole 12 fewer bases than he did the season before. That could be cause for concern for a player turning 34 years old, but Cain dealt with injuries nearly the entire way and did not have luck on his side, finishing with a career-low .301 BABIP. Cain is still among the best in center field and won his first Gold Glove in 2019, so he will still see the field plenty. His aggressive defense exposes him to injury more than some, but if he can avoid missing too many games -- and also a few more defenders when he puts the bat on the ball -- he would be in position to bounce back.

Polanco had his breakout year in 2019, silencing the critics who wondered if his 2017 efforts were mostly PED-driven. He made the absolute most out of his playing time, hitting at or near the top of a loaded Minnesota lineup that will only be stronger in 2020. The increase in power came from a change in his approach, as he got more loft to the baseball, increasing his fly ball rate by six percentage points. The one thing holding the switch-hitter back is that he is much more effective from the right side than the left. He did have ankle surgery in late November to relieve an impingement issue, which put a pause on baseball activities until early January. It will be interesting to see how the change in offseason planning affects him in the new year, if at all.

The standards to qualify as a bright spot with the Marlins have been quite low in recent seasons, but Anderson would cross that bar anywhere. He backed up his 112 wRC+ from the 2018 season with a 114 mark last season, the product of a .261/.342/.468 slash line. He also saw his HR total jump from 11 to 20. Those numbers don't exactly leap off the page, but when combined with strong defensive metrics both at third base and in right field, it's enough to make him a solidly above-average starter. While he's developed into arguably the Marlins' best player, his skill set still doesn't add up to a particularly intriguing fantasy asset given his mediocre contact and power. There's certainly value in a 26-year-old with a decent bat who is eligible at two positions, but he's held back by his tough home park and poor supporting cast.

DeJong possesses an interesting batted-ball profile. He's a fly ball hitter, which obviously benefits home runs. However, his average exit velocity is just 20th percentile, which is seemingly out of whack with hitting 30 homers, especially with power-suppressing Busch Stadium as his home. DeJong's component data is telling. His average exit velocity on fly balls is 4 mph faster than average, while he hits grounders weaker than most. This generated the 43rd-longest average fly ball distance -- well over 90th percentile -- which helped support his HR production. This not only explains the power, but also DeJong's low BABIP, as weak grounders usually result in outs. While there's no guarantee DeJong maintains that elevated fly ball exit velocity, it comes from his uppercut swing. Therefore, it's probable he continues to hit for power with a low average.

Upton missed significant time in 2019, first due to turf toe and then a bothersome knee. To be fair, any amount of time Upton misses can be classified as significant given that he had previously avoided the injured list through nine MLB seasons. Durability is a skill until it is not any longer, and Upton's body betrayed him in 2019. You almost want to throw away his entire stat line because the production was so far off from what he produced from 2016 to 2018 that it's unfair to believe this is the new norm for him. The running game is likely a thing of the past, but if he can stay healthy and return to his pre-injury levels, he stands to benefit from a strong lineup in front of him.

The juiced ball brought with it a number of surprising breakouts, and Garver's name is near the top of the list. After hitting a respectable but not particularly noteworthy .268/.335/.414 in 335 plate appearances in 2018, he managed an excellent .273/.365/.630 line last season while seeing his home run total jump from seven to 31 in just 24 more plate appearances. Only six catchers all-time have slugged at least that high in at least as many trips to the plate. Did Garver suddenly become an all-time great overnight? Probably not, but Statcast gives plenty of reason to buy the breakout, giving him an xSLG of .573 and a hard-hit rate of 50.0%. Part of Garver's success might have been the fact that he was able to stay fresh with a relatively light workload. The departure of fellow backstop Jason Castro could lead to more at-bats, but more wear-and-tear.

After signing with the Tigers, Cron is now set to play for his fourth organization in as many years, earmarked for the everyday job at first base. The 30-year-old right-handed hitter is coming off his best season, according to Statcast metrics, though his 2018 fantasy numbers were better. Specifically, Cron set personal bests in average exit velocity, Barrel% and hard-hit rate, along with an improved 21.6 K% -- his lowest mark since 2016. On paper, Cron should benefit from the change in home venue, as Comerica Park boosts right-handed power while Target Field suppresses it. As a team, Detroit's offense will be below average, but there's ample firepower at the top for Cron to hold his own in runs and RBIs, and he's likely to eclipse his previous high of 140 games played. Corner infield isn't as deep as usual, making Cron one of the better late-round options.

Walker has always been able to hit, but strikeouts and lack of defensive versatility have limited chances for an extended look at the major-league level. The trade of Paul Goldschmidt and a couple of injuries paved the way for Walker to play regularly at first base in the desert. He came through, posting an 85th percentile average exit velocity and 94th percentile hard-hit rate while dropping his strikeout rate to a career-low 25.7%. Walker also significantly lowered his chase rate while becoming more discerning in the zone, resulting in a career-best 11.1% walk rate. Assuming the Diamondbacks don't sign another solid bat, Walker should at least match last season's playing time, though if he slumps, Jake Lamb could snag some at-bats. First base isn't as deep as past seasons, rendering Walker a sneaky option for those who decide to wait after missing out on the top few tiers.

Contreras has an odd batted-ball profile for a power-hitting backstop, stroking ground balls more than half the time while exhibiting prolific power when he lofts the ball. His average exit velocity distribution screams uppercut swing. To wit, Contreras' average exit velocity on fly balls and line drives is well above average with a below-average mark on grounders. This explains a home run-per-fly ball rate above 24% in three of the last four campaigns. If Contreras can convert some grounders into fly balls, he would have 30-homer upside. Contreras outperforms his expected batting due to the above-average exit velocity on lofted balls along with 71st percentile sprint speed resulting in twice as many infield hits as the average catcher. If your draft plan entails rostering a top catcher, Contreras should be on your short list.

Lowe's batting profile is more like a corner infielder than a second baseman. He's a fly ball hitter with a high strikeout rate. Lowe hits the ball with ample authority to have plus power but playing in Tropicana Field is a detriment and the combo of low contact and fly ball outs caps Lowe's batting average. Last season, Lowe missed most of the second half with a quad injury, so an artificially high .377 BABIP didn't have a chance to regress. He has above-average speed, so the landing would probably have been soft, but he was hitting a bit over his skis. There are very few everyday players on the Rays, so expect the lefty swinger to occupy the strong side of a keystone platoon, with a chance to lose playing time if his excessive whiffs result in a slump.

Looking to fortify the top of their order, the Phillies acquired Segura from the Mariners last offseason. Despite a short stint on the IL in April, Segura's return to the senior circuit went swimmingly, as he was slashing .360/.406/.551 through May 4. However, from that point on, Segura registered a .265/.307/.396 line, finishing with a .280 average, his first season below .300 since 2015. The good news is Segura's underlying metrics were nearly identical to recent seasons, specifically contact rate, average exit velocity and launch angle. A rebound is likely, but there still are a couple of concerns. After six straight seasons with at least 20 steals, Segura swiped only 10 bags. Plus, with Didi Gregorius in town, Segura could hit in the lower half of the order. Segura's slash line should rebound, albeit with less production than a couple of years ago, especially in the stolen-base category.

Entering 2019, there were legitimate questions about Davis' ability to hit at the major-league level after he registered a paltry .175 average in 103 at-bats in 2018. Davis emphatically silenced those doubts, posting a .307/.369/.527 slash line while clubbing 22 home runs in 410 at-bats. Statcast data provided legitimacy to his performance, as Davis registered an 11.4% barrel rate and 91.4 mph average exit velocity, both well above average. As it turns out, there is little to complain about when reviewing Davis' offensive output. He hit the ball hard (41.6 Hard%) while maintaining a palatable 21.4 K% and displaying adequate patience at the plate, logging a healthy 8.4% walk rate. Things didn't go nearly as smoothly defensively, but the Mets have little choice but to find a spot for Davis to play as long as he continues to wield a potent stick.

Tommy John surgery performed on Hicks' elbow on Halloween was expected to sideline him for 8-10 months, for a July-August projected timetable, and he indicated he might be ready for full-time play by the time of the delayed Opening Day. His .250/.359/.464 rates and per-162-games averages of 31 home runs and 13 stolen bases from 2017-19 are attractive stats for when he eventually returns, but he has also missed nearly as many games (202) during that span as he has played (284), which casts doubt upon such a quick recovery or his ability to stay healthy regularly even after his return. Unless your team allows an expansive injured list, Hicks might be better left to the sidelines awaiting positive notes on his recovery.

While Smith led the majors in stolen bases last season with 46, he was not a big net-positive in the rotisserie game, finishing with roughly $5 earned in 12-team mixed leagues. By real-world measures, Smith was essentially a replacement-level player. He legged out 19 infield hits, but still managed just a .227 average while fanning in about 25% of his plate appearances. Smith does not walk much and the power is pretty much nonexistent, as evidenced by his 13 career home runs in more than 1,600 major league plate appearances. Smith's average exit velocity, hard-hit rate, xBA, xSLG and xwOBA all ranked in the bottom 5% of the league, per Statcast. In pretty much every non-rotisserie format, Smith is undraftable. In roto leagues he's in the mix, but only as a desperation play if you miss out on speed early. Beware that the threat of reduced playing time is very real, even in Seattle.

Tommy John surgery cost Perez the entirety of 2019, and we haven't seen him play since September 2018. Still, coming into spring training, all signs were positive regarding his recovery. The Royals, who had made Perez one of the game's true workhorse catchers before his injury, might even give him time at first base, which should alleviate some of the concerns about physical wear and tear (not to mention add another position to his eligibility list). Perez's extreme fly ball shift in the three years before his surgery suggested he should be able to be one of the better power sources from the catcher-eligible pool. His free-swinging ways are a problem in points leagues, where he might have a tougher time finishing as a top-10 performer at the position. Monitor his health this spring, but there's every reason to believe that he will rebound.

Santana's 28 homers and .534 SLG seemingly came out of nowhere, but his average flyball distance in 2017 portended to twice as many homers (he hit four in 178 plate appearances) and his 2019 average distance easily backed the breakout. That said, with the likelihood he will play most of his home games with the roof closed in a new climate-controlled venue, some regression is likely. Still, Santana also does something few other first basemen can do -- steal bases. He was 21-for-27 (78 percent) last season, a good enough clip to keep earning the green light. Santana's plate skills are lacking (29.5% K% and 4.9% BB% last season), but a 90th-percentile average exit velocity means good things usually happen when he hits the ball. Santana is slated to be the Rangers regular center fielder, but in fantasy leagues he can help accrue steals from the first-base position.

The Phillies signed McCutchen in an attempt to bolster their leadoff spot. Through his first 59 games, the veteran was getting on base at a 38% clip and was on pace for well over 100 runs. Unfortunately, his season was cut short when he tore the ACL in his left knee during a fluke rundown, instigated when Jean Segura failed to run out a popup with McCutchen on first base. Surgery was required to repair the damage, though McCutchen is expected to make a full recovery. The 34-year-old outfielder is again ticketed for the top spot in the Phillies' lineup, playing mostly left field and possibly some designated hitter. McCutchen displayed strong skills across the board, sporting 91st percentile sprint speed pre-injury. Even so, he was only 2-for-3 in steals during the truncated campaign. If healthy, his opportunities could increase with Joe Girardi now at the helm.

From a real baseball sense, Hosmer is fighting an uphill battle, as he will always be judged relative to his exorbitant contact. In the fantasy realm, he's at a disadvantage since he doesn't provide the power many feel is a requisite for his position. The combination of these factors usually (and unfairly) penalizes Hosmer on draft day. On rosters looking to balance risk with stability, Hosmer provides the latter. Granted, much of his production is volume-driven, as he's averaged 159 games for the past five seasons. Still, Hosmer has averaged just 22 homers over that span, albeit it with a sneaky 84 runs and 92 RBIs. Last season, Hosmer knocked in 99 teammates. With an improved lineup, eclipsing the century mark in RBIs for the second time is plausible. Since he hardly runs anymore (0-for-3 last season in attempted steals), Hosmer has little to no upside. But like a solid hardwood floor, he offers durability and reliability.

Votto is not aging gracefully at first base in Cincinnati. He is still getting 600-plus plate appearances -- reaching that threshold in six of the past seven seasons -- but the batting average has decreased in each of the past four years while his ability to make contact is getting incrementally worse. Just two seasons ago, Votto struck out in only 12% of his plate appearances, but that number rose to 20% last year. We saw him post his lowest OBP of his career (.357) in 2019, and his walk rate also fell to its worst rate since 2008. Votto is still receiving a similar amount of pitches in the zone, but last year he expanded his zone like he did earlier in his career, and he was punished for it. There is little optimism for a late-career bounce-back.

Edman doesn't have a firm position entering 2020, but he also plays for a Cardinals team that likes to shuffle players around the field and has a thinner roster on the offensive side than at this time a year ago. Thanks to his contact-driven approach, he scored the 41st-most fantasy points of any player from July 1 forward, and while his .346 BABIP is likely to regress, he's capable enough with both the bat and his legs to contribute on the lower tiers of mixed leagues to weigh in all fantasy leagues. Edman begins 2020 both second- and third-base eligible and could add the outfield to his in-season qualification list, so keep him tucked away as a safety-net player in the late rounds.

McMahon forced his way into regular duty across three different positions for the Rockies last season, posting top-250 across-the-board fantasy production. In the process, he enjoyed almost identical righty/lefty splits (.331 and .326, respectively), though his Coors/road splits were wide and he hit the ball on the ground more than 50% of the time, tempering some enthusiasm. McMahon's major league-high 26.2% HR/FB rate after the All-Star break also suggested he could struggle to repeat his career-high 24 homers. As he should play a fair amount between first and second base again, he'll be a worthwhile middle infield option in mixed leagues, but it'll probably require an elevation of his launch angle for him to take the next step.

Expectations were high after Voit compiled a .333/.405/.689 line with the Yankees to end the 2018 campaign. He was trending toward a respectable follow-up season last summer, slashing .278/.392/.493 on July 30. Voit was then shelved with a sports hernia and wasn't the same when he came back, posting an anemic .200/.319/.338 line after returning on Aug. 30. Voit's opposite-field approach is ideal for Yankee Stadium as he's only pulled 13 of his 40 career homers. A high strikeout rate suggests his average should settle closer to 2019 than 2018, but a high walk rate helps soften the blow in OBP and points leagues. Voit enters the 2020 season healthy with the inside track on the starting job at first base. The Yankees have other options to cycle through but his on-base ability with plus power should keep him in the lineup nearly every day early on.

Ramos has consistently hit the ball hard, averaging a 90 mph exit velocity since the stat has been measured. The problem is that his contact is coming with an alarming decrease in loft. Ramos' average launch angle in 2019 was nonexistent -- 0.0 -- as 62% of his batted balls were grounders. Ramos' most frequent batted-ball outcome was a pulled ground ball to the left side into a shift, but he hits the ball hard enough to get through shifts and has maintained a strong batting average for the catching position. The ground ball thing is not a fluke, as Ramos has a 55% career ground ball rate, but 2019 was the first time since 2012 that his ground balls outpaced his fly balls by a 3-to-1 margin. The Mets are moving him down in the lineup, and you should move him down in your rankings.

Choo turns 38 during the 2020 season, but you would never know it based on his production in recent years. He has had at least 600 plate appearances in four of the past five seasons. He continues to hit with authority, while displaying outstanding on-base skills. He even surprised us with 15 steals last season after reaching double digits only once in the prior six seasons. Choo is a good reminder that stolen bases are not all about speed, as his average sprint speed was identical to those of Miguel Sano and Jose Abreu in 2019. His hitting prowess can be neutralized by left-handed pitchers, but he maximizes his production against righties with a near-.900 OPS over the past two seasons. The Rangers have a new stadium, which will likely alter the run environment, but this is very safe production to roster as Choo heads into free agency in 2021.

Though Gregorius scuffled in an unspectacular 2019 season, there's reason to be optimistic about him moving forward. Despite some rust while working his way back from Tommy John surgery, Gregorius posted the second-best ISO (.204) and AB/HR (20.3) marks of his career. His .238 batting average wasn't pretty, but some bad luck was involved as he suffered from a career-worst .237 BABIP. The Yankee Stadium factor must be considered when projecting the shortstop's power numbers, but subtract a lopsided 2018 campaign and his home/road homer splits during his tenure as a Yankee were dead even (35/35). Besides, Philadelphia is far from the worst place for a lefty hitter to play, and it bears mentioning that Gregorius' barrel rate (5.9%), average exit velocity (88.2 mph) and xSLG (.408) all reached career peaks last season. That bodes well for a bounce-back 2020 campaign even as he adjusts to his new surroundings.

A rebuild allows a team to give second chances to players who previously showed little, in hopes that one or two of them will still work out. Dozier leapt at that opportunity in his age-27 season, hitting an impressive .279/.348/.522 in 139 games after entering the year with a .228/.279/.388 line over 110 contests. It did take a .339 BABIP to get there, though that's not an exceptionally high number, and Statcast suggests he overachieved by only a moderate amount, giving him a .261 xBA and a .471 xSLG. If Dozier regresses to those marks this season, he won't be a particularly interesting fantasy option, especially given that he will still have to fight against a tough home park and a mediocre lineup. However, he will at least be a capable cheaper option at either third base or in the outfield.

Among all second basemen through their respective age-25 seasons, Odor's 136 career home runs dwarfs the rest of the field, coming in 47 ahead of second place. That sounds like the start of a Hall of Fame career, not the career of a player whose future as a starter appeared to be in serious doubt late last season. The rest of Odor's stat line reveals why the Rangers have grown frustrated with him. While he hit at least 30 homers in three of the last four seasons, he also hit .205 or worse in two of the last three. In 2019, his K% shot up to 30.6 as he managed a poor .205/.283/.439 slash line and played below-average defense. He still looks like a starter for now, but don't be surprised if this is the year Odor moves to the bench.

After nearly two calendar years bouncing between Triple-A and the Rangers, Calhoun finally settled into a regular job after the All-Star break, batting .265/.328/.540 with 16 home runs and 35 RBI in the 57 games following his July 25 promotion. That locked him into a regular job -- finally! -- entering 2020, where his combination of contact and fly ball stroke give him plenty of breakthrough potential. This is a player as capable of reaching a .290 batting average or 30 homers or -- gasp -- both. He's well worth stashing as your fifth outfielder in the hopes he realizes it.

Newman put himself on the map in 2019 with a solid all-around campaign that included a .308/.353/.446 slash line, 12 HRs and 16 SBs. The power output was surprising, as Newman had totaled only 15 homers in 1,630 career minor-league at-bats and posted a meager 2.1% barrel rate, 24.4% hard-hit rate and 84.7 mph average exit velocity with the Pirates last season. However, his proficient hitting and base-running are backed by promising data. Newman ranked in the 90th percentile last season with a .291 xBA and in the 84th percentile with a sprint speed of 28.5 ft/s. He also displayed superb contact skills, registering an 87.0% contact rate and 11.7 K%, each ranking in the top five among qualified hitters. His potential to hit for a high average while amassing double-digit steals make Newman worth a look in the mid-to-late rounds of fantasy drafts.

Garcia's year-over-year BABIP fluctuations explain his variable annual batting averages, and it casts some doubt on him being a consistent weekly-league fantasy option. He hits lefties well and will call a homer-friendly venue home in Miller Park. These are things that can be exploited more in ESPN's standard daily formats. Garcia is also faster than you realize and has routinely ranked among the top 10-15% in Statcast's sprint speed. As such, another run at double-digit steals isn't entirely out of the question. Regard him as a good late-round pick or a fifth outfielder.

A .291/.413/.553, 8-homer, 28-RBI start in his first 40 games for Triple-A Oklahoma City, coupled with Austin Barnes' groin injury, earned Smith a two-week audition with the Dodgers in May/June, during which time he belted two homers and opened many eyes. Barnes' continued struggles paved the way for Smith's more permanent promotion in late July, after which he started 39 of the Dodgers' final 57 games while batting .250/.335/.556 with 12 homers and 36 RBIs. Before you embrace him as a budding superstar, though, note how much of his fantasy value was tied to home runs in the rabbit-baseball year. In a similar offensive environment, he could challenge for HR lead at catcher, something that would make him an easy top-five fantasy backstop. However, the holes in his swing could lead to inconsistency, some growing pains and perhaps a low batting average. Smith is a great dynasty pick, but be careful not to have outrageous expectations.

In his age-30 season, Canha emerged as one of Oakland's top offensive weapons, posting a .273/.396/.517 slash line and swatting 26 HRs. His 146 wRC+ led the team and ranked 12th in the majors among players with at least 350 PA. Canha did many things well, registering a solid 9.5% barrel rate and 89.1 mph average exit velocity while compiling an outstanding 13.5 BB%. He kept his strikeouts in line, too, finishing with a tolerable 21.5 K%. Canha's most notable flaw was a .221 BA against left-handed pitching -- well below the .282 mark he posted in 2018. Expected improvement in that area in 2020 should provide some padding against a potential drop in his .297 average against righties. A lack of steals and a pitcher-friendly home park limit Canha's fantasy ceiling, but he's worth a look in most leagues, particularly those that count OBP.

A popular sleeper pick entering 2019, Hampson struggled with making contact early (28.1% first-half strikeout rate) and couldn't squeeze his way into a crowded lineup, but enjoyed a late surge that will probably earn him similar attention this year. In the final five weeks of the season, he slashed .330/.377/.526, hit five homers, stole 10 bases and started 23 of 29 Rockies games between three different positions (second base, shortstop and center field). That was probably closer to Hampson's true self, a contact-oriented (80.4% rate), speedy package that could make a significant impact if he gets everyday at-bats. The Rockies would be wise to find places for him across any of those three spots again, and his spring progress could do a lot to push the needle up from his current draft stock: A late-round sleeper with dual eligibility (second base/outfield).

Wong has long been a fantasy tease, flashing the power-speed goodness so desired in a fantasy lineup. Not to mention, skipper Mike Shildt appears to be more reliant on running, benefiting Wong. The problem is his supporting data is risky. Yes, some players thrive despite a low hard-hit rate, but their margin for error is thin, resulting in a wide range of outcomes. Wong's average exit velocity is low. This may help him beat out grounders and lead to some dying quails in the outfield, but it's not a profile to elicit confidence. That said, Wong was 24-for-28 in the stolen base department last season, an enticing total in an era featuring dwindling pilfers. Wong's Gold Glove defense will keep him in the lineup though he's likely to hit low in the order, limiting his ability to compile counting stats outside of steals.

A Statcast-hard-contact darling in his two big-league seasons with the Indians, Diaz was a player in whom the Rays took a chance that paid off handsomely last offseason. He started 41 of the team's first 44 games shuffling between the corner infield spots and DH and hit nine home runs in 180 trips to the plate, matching his entire 2017-18 total between the majors and minors. Unfortunately, injuries -- a hand contusion, hamstring tightness and a foot contusion -- cost him a trio of IL stints totaling 79 lost Rays games thereafter, with health now the bigger question surrounding him entering 2020. Diaz should factor prominently at third base for the team, with good odds of matching or even exceeding his per-game rates from 2019, but he's more of a speculative fantasy corner infielder for mixed leagues with the injury and defensive questions he faces.

Castro upped his production in his second season with the Marlins, establishing career highs with 22 home runs, 86 RBIs and a .166 ISO. His peripherals fell in line with his career norms; Castro rarely walked (4.1 BB%), kept his strikeouts down (16.4 K%) and made good contact (82.5% contact rate). The veteran's steady floor is his most desirable asset from a fantasy perspective. During the past four seasons, his xBA fell between .262 and .271, and his xSLG remained in the .407-.432 range. Those numbers are pretty near league average, which is a fine term to describe Castro's game as a whole. After the Marlins declined his team option, the Nationals scooped him up, and he is likely to start at second base. The move away from Miami could boost his numbers slightly, but it's best to expect another season of average production and treat anything more as a bonus.

Promoted by the Rangers in mid-August following the injury to Nomar Mazara, Solak provided the big club an offensive jolt, even emerging as its regular cleanup hitter for a spell in September. Some of it was the product of good fortune: his .354 BABIP, and 32% Statcast hard-contact rate scream "regression candidate," though in his defense, Solak's patience and keen eye at the plate could make him a sneaky-good pick in a points league. Unfortunately, while he should make the team and play fairly regularly, he'll be DH-only in fantasy and might not escape that designation, due to his poor defense.

The Reds seemed to go out of their way this offseason to stockpile talent that blocks Senzel's path to playing time, which is a shame considering how bright his prospect star was at this time just one year ago. Considering the barrage of ailments he has suffered over the past three seasons -- a pair of ankle sprains, vertigo, a fractured right index finger, migraines and a season-ending torn labrum in his shoulder in September, among other minor bumps and bruises -- it's an understandable strategy. It allows him the opportunity to prove himself in a super-utility role ( la Scott Kingery in Philadelphia) rather than trusting him initially on an everyday basis. Senzel showed enough pop and speed between ailments to warrant a stash even in redraft formats, but a strong spring would do a lot to make him a more reliable mid-round pick.

Grichuk enjoyed a career year in terms of run production, setting career highs in homers, RBIs and runs scored. The batting average and lack off running game held down his value, and we should expect more of the same in 2020. Grichuk is not very accepting of walks and has a lot of swing-and-miss in his game. He struggles to hit for average and get on base against righty pitchers. His run-production opportunities will be dependent on where he hits in the lineup. Chances are, Grichuk will hit in the bottom half of the order, unless he can supplant Travis Shaw from his spot in the lineup. The quality of his contact took a step back last season for the first time in three years, so that bears watching.

Chavis' rookie campaign was akin to that of many young batters with respect to contact issues and adjustments. Opposing pitchers got him to chase high heat before he learned to lay off. Then, right-handed hurlers with the ability to place sweeping sliders off the outside edge were able to get him to fish. Chavis was in the process of making that adjustment when he was shelved with an oblique injury, ending his freshman campaign in mid-August. Entering 2020, Chavis is expected to be healthy. If he can control the zone better, he has plenty of pop and could be a solid contributor to a still-deep lineup. Playing-time opportunities include the small side of a first-base platoon with Mitch Moreland and competing with Jose Peraza, Marco Hernandez and maybe Dustin Pedroia for action at the keystone.

The Yankees lost starting 2018 third baseman Miguel Andujar to a shoulder injury early, but they didn't skip a beat, with Urshela filling in admirably on defense (expected) and offense (wait? what?!). Playing in his third organization in the past two seasons, Urshela shattered his previous professional bests for a single year with 21 home runs, .534 slugging percentage, .219 isolated power and a .314 batting average, with boosts in both his line-drive and hard-contact rates lending legitimacy to the performance. The Yankees' concerns about Andujar's defense should give Urshela a long leash in the race for their 2020 third base gig, so Urshela should remain a regular in the absence of a bad spring. He'll probably regress after such an unexpectedly good year, but remains a worthwhile mixed league corner infielder.

A shoulder injury that ultimately led to season-ending surgery on May 20 ruined Andujar's 2019, and the 12-game sample he delivered provided no hints as to his future value. Besides the lengthy recovery from that ailment, he faces another critical obstacle to success: poor defense, which clouds his 2020 role on a Yankees team where Gio Urshela excelled at the hot corner in his absence. Andujar is untested at either first base or in left field. For fantasy, he is listed as DH-only due to his limited play last year. He could rebound with a stat line not far shy of his 2018 breakthrough, but there are a lot of questions here that make him more of a mid-to-late-round pick.

For most players, blasting 79 homers before their 25th birthday would be an accomplishment, but for Mazara, it's disappointing. Consistency is also usually lauded for a player, but even though Mazara has posted an OPS between .739 and .787 each season of his four-year career, the narrative is that the former top prospect has not developed as hoped. Though, to be fair, he did post career highs in batting average and slugging last season. Skills-wise, Mazara is league average across the board, from contact to exit velocity to sprint speed. Maybe a change in scenery can trigger some improvement as the Rangers dealt Mazara to the South Side of Chicago, where he's ticketed to patrol right field. Although it's still too early in his career to pigeonhole Mazara as a platoon bat, he's headed that way with a career 103 wRC+ versus right-handers compared with 59 facing southpaws.

Renfroe was traded from one club with a logjam in the corner outfield to another. That said, with the Rays, he should lose less playing time, in large part due to his excellent defense, an underappreciated aspect of his game. Jose Martinez and Yoshi Tsutsugo will compete with Renfroe for outfield action, but neither are the defender he is, nor do they possess the power. The main hole in Renfroe's game is contact as he fanned at a career-worst 31% clip last season. However, he's an extreme flyball hitter with an average exit velocity on flyballs of 95.9 mph, well above the 93.0 mph league mark. While this supports bountiful long balls, the tandem of strikeouts and flyball outs yield a low batting average while limiting run production relative to the homer total. He's also a liability in OBP leagues with a career 7% walk rate.

Peralta generated some buzz during the 2018 campaign by revamping his swing and raising his power output to a career-high 30 home runs. In 2019, he maintained the increased fly ball rate (18.6%) that coincided with the power surge, but both his hard-hit rate and barrel rate dipped closer to pre-2018 levels. In turn, he slugged only 12 long balls, finishing with a 31.8 AB/HR ratio that fell in line with his career norm. A shoulder injury that hampered Peralta all season (and prematurely ended his campaign in early September) likely contributed to the regression, but it's also a gamble to assume his 2018 production was anything more than an outlier. Peralta can be safely counted on for steady hitting -- particularly against right-handers -- and double-digit homers, but it will take a leap of faith to count on above-average numbers in the power department.

In 2018, some naysayers had concerns about Carpenter's shoulder inhibiting his ability to hit for power. Those critics were silenced with a career year. What goes up must come down, however, and that is what happened to Carpenter in 2019 as his production took a tumble. The shoulder did not fail him, but back and foot problems did, causing him to fall below 550 plate appearances for the first time since 2012. When a hitter's core and base fail him, the results are going to suffer. It makes it difficult to hit with the quality of contact necessary to be successful. Carpenter's exit velocity and launch angle fell more than two percentage points with the injuries. A repeat of 2018 is unlikely, but you can expect something in the 2015-17 average range, assuming his health issues are behind him.

Last season represented a step forward for Swanson, but is that it, or is there another level yet to come? Swanson ranked 10th among qualified hitters in line-drive rate last season (25.8%) and Statcast says he deserved to hit 20 points higher than he actually did in 2019. Statcast data is more descriptive than predictive, but the batted-ball numbers do provide reason for optimism moving forward. Swanson is now entering his age-26 season and still graded out as a below-league-average hitter last season, even with his improvement. Shortstop has gotten incredibly deep -- deeper than any position in fantasy baseball -- and Swanson tends to get lost in the shuffle. However, there is playing-time stability here and Atlanta should frequently turn over the batting order. There's potentially some profit to be made using a late-round pick on Swanson to fill the middle-infield spot.

Grisham climbed two competitive levels and rode .381/.471/.776 rates in 34 games at Triple-A San Antonio into an August promotion to the Brewers, after which he started 37 of 53 games -- despite joining a crowded outfield. He continued to show good patience and pop. However, his 26.2% strikeout rate raised some concerns about his consistency and full-year batting average, and a trade to the Padres did take him out of one of the most HR-friendly venues in baseball (Miller Park) and land him in one that leans more toward pitchers (Petco Park). Grisham should grab a regular job for his new team, though, and his 25-HR power and double-digit SB ability makes him worth a No. 5 OF/late-round selection in rotisserie leagues.

Early in spring training, Seager injured his left thumb diving for a ball. Surgery was necessary, delaying his 2019 debut until late May. By this time, there were reports the 2019 ball was different, adding several feet to a well-hit fly ball. Seager's underlying power metrics were such he could benefit more than most. It took a while to manifest, but sure enough, Seager went on a tear after the break, hitting 17 second-half home runs. He finished with a career-best .229 ISO. Seager's bat still has some pop, and aside from last spring's fluke injury, he's been quite durable, averaging 157 games per season from 2012-18, helping to compile runs and RBIs. Corner infield isn't as deep as normal; in fact, it's shallower than middle infield. He's not sexy, but Seager can still provide reliable cheap power, albeit with a low batting average.

Madrigal's hit tool and raw speed are exceptional, a rare combination for a prospect, and his 2019 results across three competitive levels back it: he struck out only 16 times in 532 trips to the plate, and stole 35 bases in 48 attempts. The White Sox claim he'll get a long look in their spring second base race, and considering the team might have wild-card aspirations, it's entirely possible he'll run away with the gig. But even if Madrigal's big-league debut waits until May or June -- remember those service time worries! -- he should immediately become one of the more attractive speedsters in fantasy, and one of the better ones in points leagues too because of his elite contact. A top-15 case among second basemen is an easy case to make if he can garner the requisite at-bats.

Goodrum led all Tigers position players in fWAR last season with 1.9 in 112 games, playing everywhere on the field outside of the battery positions. The majority of his time was spent between shortstop and the outfield, but Goodrum also carries second base eligibility heading into 2020 with bonus 1B eligibility in leagues with a 15-game minimum. He struck out at a 29.2% clip last season, and a K-rate pushing 30% puts a firm cap on his BA. Goodrum does not have the power typically associated with this level of swinging and missing, but he has 92nd-percentile sprint speed and puts those wheels to use just enough to be relevant in deeper mixed leagues (12-for-15 on stolen-base attempts last season). The multi-position eligibility certainly helps his case. This skill set will not move the needle much, but there is value in the speed and flexibility he offers.

In 2017, Schoop chased considerably less and results ensued, as he posted his best season to date. Unfortunately, Schoop reverted to his aggressive ways, swinging at more pitches out of the zone, and his numbers suffered. The drop in production cost Schoop playing time the past two years, to the point the Twins designated him for assignment following a 2019 campaign during which he played just 121 games, his lowest total since 2015. Schoop still possesses plus power, fueled by an average exit velocity on fly balls higher than the league norm. Schoop is just 28 years old, young enough to make adjustments and approach 2017's level. He picked an ideal place for the endeavor, signing with Detroit, where he's earmarked for regular playing time at the keystone, hitting in the meat of the order. He's worth a speculative dart if you need some cheap pop.

After a year-plus of injury troubles, Hays got a cup of coffee with an Orioles team bereft of talent at the big-league level, filling the five pertinent rotisserie categories despite a contact rate out of character with his minor league track record. He'll face similarly light competition for at-bats entering 2020, but for all of the volume-driven appeal, he might not yet be ready to perform at the level of a top-30 fantasy outfielder. Hays is well worth the roll of the dice as your fifth mixed league outfielder, or as an AL-only mid-to-late rounder, but let him prove himself with a full year of success before you invest more.

Any discussion of surprising feats during the 2019 season must include Vazquez's out-of-nowhere power explosion. After hitting only 10 home runs through his first 922 major-league at-bats, Vazquez slugged 23 long balls in 482 trips to the plate last season, seventh most among catchers. The transformation can largely be attributed to adjustments in his batting stance and the juiced baseball. While Vazquez's fly ball rate (25.1%) and average launch angle (12.9 degrees) remained relatively constant, his hard-hit rate jumped significantly to a career-best 33.6%, and his 6.2% barrel rate more than tripled his paltry 2018 mark. There are plenty of reasons to be skeptical of the 5-foot-9 backstop's growth -- he outperformed both his xBA and xSLG -- but even with some power regression, he should see enough volume (thanks in part to his ability to play multiple infield positions) to be viable as a first catcher.

Much of Profar's disappointing 2019 season can be directly attributed to moving from one of the best hitting venues to one of the poorest. In 2018, Profar hit .254 with 20 homers. Translated to Oakland, that's .236 with 16 homers. In 2019 with the Athletics, Profar hit .218, a drop of 18 points from the adjusted mark. If a batter hits .270 instead of .288, hardly anyone would bat an eyelash. Profar's added power last season reflects the funky baseball. Profar enters his age-27 season with his third team in three years as the Padres acquired the former top prospect in the offseason. Petco Park plays similarly to RingCentral Coliseum, so Profar should be expected to bat close to the .236 expected mark discussed above with similar power. Bottom line is Profar is a below-average hitter, only useful in the deeper formats.

A couple of years ago, moving from Angels Stadium to Chase Field would have been a boon for the lefty-swinging Calhoun. But the home run boundary was lowered in Anaheim, while a humidor was installed in the desert, flip-flopping the venues and then some. Last season, Calhoun blasted a career-high 33 homers but curiously only 16 at home. He was no doubt helped by the 2019 baseball, as his average fly ball distance was by far a personal best despite no change to his Statcast power metrics. Not only is Calhoun unlikely to match last season's power surge, his strikeout rate increased for the third straight season. Additionally, while he was never a burner, Calhoun's sprint speed is in decline and he finished in the 30th percentile last season. Calhoun's defense will keep him in the lineup, but beware a low batting average with waning power.

Akiyama, signed by the Reds this offseason as a free agent out of Japan, possesses a good overall blend of skills -- defense included -- but not one that registers as outstanding. He'll probably settle as the team's regular center fielder due to his above-average range, arm and raw speed. From 2017-19, Akiyama slashed .316/.398/.514 while averaging 23 homers and 14 stolen bases in Japan, and while those won't necessarily directly translate in the States, they show a skillset that might make a significantly greater impact in points leagues than rotisserie, especially if he continues to walk frequently and draws a top-two-in-the-order lineup spot. In those points formats, Akiyama is a worthy final-outfielder flier, and a strong spring would boost that value and make him that caliber player in roto, too.

Dickerson was on the IL a week into the season due to a shoulder strain. That set the tone for his entire 2019; Dickerson also missed time with groin and finger injuries before a fractured left foot sidelined him for good. In between, Dickerson was excellent, hitting .300 for the fourth time in his career -- the second time not playing home games of Coors Field -- with his highest ISO ever. His strikeout rate ticked up, but 20.1% is still quite good in this era. Given all the missed time last season, it's easy to forget about Dickerson and how consistently good he's been with the bat. Previously, injuries had not been a major problem, with Dickerson logging at least 533 PA in each of the three seasons prior to 2019, so he's arguably not much more of an injury risk than any other position player. After signing a two-year deal with the Marlins, Dickerson is slated to play every day.

Puig began and ended the 2019 campaign in opposite corners of the Buckeye State after the Reds dealt him to the Indians at the trade deadline in the Trevor Bauer deal. Prior to the move, the 30-year-old was slashing .252/.303/.475. He posted a .297/.377/.423 line after. For the season, Puig's numbers were consistent with his career norms. With Cleveland, Puig's on-base skills improved, but his power dipped. However, while Puig hit only two homers after the trade, he clubbed 15 doubles. The venue change likely contributed, but he was also snake bit based on average fly ball distance. Steals have always been an underappreciated aspect of Puig's arsenal, and a career-high 19 last season bodes well for his value in a category where the overall numbers are dwindling. The hope for immense upside is over, replaced with an often-discounted but stable floor.

By some measures, Adames was the third-most-valuable position player on the Rays last season, mostly on account of his stellar defense at shortstop. He started slowly with the bat but turned it on over the final two months, finishing with a respectable .278/.340/.467 batting line (115 wRC+) after the All-Star break. Adames shaved four percentage points off his strikeout rate from the first half to the second half and added more than 40 points to his ISO. It's important to remember that he was still just 23 years old for most of last season and was once a top prospect in the system. The Rays now have uber-prospect Wander Franco waiting in the wings, but if Adames can hit like he did in the second half, he could force the team to break Franco in at second base.

Pollock has struggled with injuries since his breakout season in 2015, having failed to eclipse the 500-plate-appearance plateau since that year. His overall skills remain strong, but his ability to showcase those skills has been compromised by injuries to his elbow, thumb and groin. Pollock has the skills and athleticism to go 20-20 in a season, as he did back in 2015 when he was on the field enough to do so. Around the injuries and ups and downs in the counting categories, Pollock has had very little variance in his triple-slash categories, both in terms of his actual BA/OBP/SLG and his expected performances in those statistical categories based on his quality of contact. The Dodgers' lineup is loaded with talent, so Pollock cannot afford another injury-riddled season, as he may not get back into the lineup. Big contracts do not always guarantee playing time.

When healthy, Polanco possesses a power/speed skill set that plays well in fantasy. Unfortunately, the 28-year-old hasn't been healthy since injuring his shoulder late in the 2018 campaign and is not guaranteed to be 100 percent when the 2020 season begins. Polanco attempted to return from the injury in 2019 but logged only 166 PA before being shut down. When he did play, Polanco struggled to hit the ball, as both his contact rate (68.0%) and strikeout rate (29.3%) were easily the worst marks of his career. If there's any good news to take from the abbreviated campaign, it's that Polanco's barrel rate (9.6%) and average exit velocity (89.4 mph) remained considerably above league average. Polanco may be worth a late-round dart throw for those in mixed leagues looking to address a homer/steals deficit with one pick, but it would behoove such gamblers to monitor his health closely.

A 35-homer, 22-steal season for Triple-A Albuquerque earned Hilliard a five-week cup of coffee with the Rockies to conclude 2019, with which he showed similar contributions with seven homers and a 2-for-2 performance attempting steals in 27 games. Much of it seemed to be Coors-influenced, though, and Hilliard's batted-ball and hard-contact metrics suggested he was performing a bit above his true talent. He'll be in the mix for a reserve role for the big club this spring, but would only warrant greater than a speculative NL-only pick if he emerges with at least a share of one of their outfield jobs.

La Stella entered 2019 firmly in a reserve role, having recorded a .264/.345/.366 line with just 10 career homers in parts of five seasons while never coming to the plate more than 360 times in a year. A fractured tibia cost him most of the final three months of last season and prevented him from reaching a new high in plate appearances, but his performance when healthy vaulted him into a whole new level. Over 80 games he hit .295/.346/.486 with 16 homers and a tiny 8.7 K%. Breakouts at his age are certainly surprising, but Statcast backs up his success, giving him a .296 xBA and a .482 xSLG. It's hard not to like a player who now has decent power to go along with excellent contact ability. With a regular role at second base open, La Stella is worth consideration this draft season.

In a season during which the Yankees sent a record number of players to the injured list, Gardner was a rock. He finished third on the team in plate appearances, behind DJ LeMahieu and Gleyber Torres, and had his best season by wRC+ since 2012. Thanks in no small part to the reduced drag on the big-league baseball, Gardner finished just two homers shy of 30, with 16 of his 28 coming away from Yankee Stadium. His running waned, but he was still plenty efficient on his 12 attempts in his age-35 season. He was a free agent for several months after the 2019 season, and those few months of uncertainty have driven down his ADP, certainly lower than it should be. A case can be made that Gardner, back in the middle of the New York lineup after re-upping on a one-year deal, should go inside the top 200 picks.

Despite a September swoon, Kelly demonstrated why the Diamondbacks acquired the backstop as one of the cornerstones in the Paul Goldschmidt deal. Kelly's .826 OPS was a respectable fifth among catchers with at least 300 plate appearances, while his 18 homers tied for 10th at the position. His defense improved, and Kelly finished with two defensive runs saved. An 88th-percentile framing grade was the driving force as his 55th-percentile pop time was just a little better than average. At the dish, Kelly's 21.6 K% was higher than previous levels, though a significant jump to a 13.2 BB% eases concerns. After playing about half the time last season, Kelly is in line for a bump in playing time, but with Stephen Vogt signed as a backup, Kelly won't play as much as some regulars. Still, he's a back-end option in one-catcher formats.

After a breakthrough 2018 campaign in which Nimmo posted a career-best .887 OPS, the 26-year-old outfielder broke camp as the Mets' starting center fielder. He was off to a sluggish start, slashing .200/.344/.323 on May 22 when he when he was put on the IL with a stiff neck. Tests revealed a bulging disc and whiplash, incurred during an outfield collision in mid-April. The injury had been bothering Nimmo, no doubt contributing to his struggles. He didn't return until rosters expanded, slashing a much-improved .262/.430/.565, drawing 20 walks to 23 strikeouts in 93 plate appearances. He swatted five homers down the stretch, stealing a pair of bags as well. The Mets acquired Jake Marisnick in the offseason, a natural platoon partner for Nimmo. However, Nimmo posted a 1.190 OPS facing southpaws last season so he may be given the chance at everyday at-bats.

Santana's overall numbers look a bit like a bounce-back to his breakout 2017 season, but when you consider he had 13 homers, 33 RBIs and 48 runs scored along with a .270 batting average by early June, the excitement fades a bit. A bum elbow certainly contributed to his poor finish, as he hit .231/.320/.385 the rest of the way with a 36% strikeout rate. He has an established track record of hitting the ball well in between all the swings and misses. He has some of the best expected results on batted-ball contact in baseball, but those events are too few and far between with the growing strikeout rate. Santana will compete for at-bats in the Indians' outfield during spring training.

Riley debuted in mid-May last season and got off to a hot start, hitting .280/.333/.596 with 14 homers over his first 42 games. It all went wrong from there, however, as he slumped to an awful .150/.203/.292 line with just four homers over his final 38 contests. His 42.3 K% over that latter stretch was untenably high, though his 32.2% mark while things were going well wasn't exactly good either. Riley should have a clear path to playing time at third base this season with Josh Donaldson gone, if not as the team's designated hitter. He's still just 22 years old, so there's certainly a chance things go better in his sophomore season. His combination of big raw power and contact concerns is right in line with his prospect reports, however, so there's plenty of risk that the swing-and-miss issues will remain prevalent in 2020.

It seemed like the perfect marriage: a high-contact hitter with a low 35% ground ball rate in Coors Field. Enter Murphy's Law, which states that anything that can go wrong will go wrong. The first weekend of the season, Murphy fractured his left index finger diving for a ball, and it was all downhill from there. He returned about four weeks later but wasn't right for the rest of the season. Murphy's average exit velocity was its lowest since Statcast began its tracking in 2015. Moreover, his line drive and fly ball rates dropped while his strikeouts grew. Even though Coors Field is better for hits than power, Murphy posted his lowest average since 2009. Murphy is currently tops on Colorado's depth chart at first base, though the Rockies do have some younger (and arguably better) options than a veteran entering his age-35 season. Murphy is in play in deeper leagues and formats with daily moves.

It's a good thing San Diego signed Myers to a long-term contract to (checks notes) serve as a bench player? Myers stands to see his playing time take another hit this year with the acquisitions of Tommy Pham and Trent Grisham to the outfield, and for good reason. Myers has been a disappointment the past two seasons, with average production. The contract is friendly enough that he could be traded to another organization, but until that happens, be very concerned about his ability to get enough playing time to even sniff what he did just two seasons ago. The expected statistics tell us not to look for a return to what he once was and to recognize what he is now: just an average player with a recognizable name.

Narvaez had a career-best season at the plate, taking advantage of the extra playing time Seattle provided him to reward them handsomely in run production. His ability to hit for average and get on base were obvious even in limited duty in previous seasons, but he was able to extend that out with extra playing time, and he added more loft to his swing to take full advantage of the bouncy baseball. While his average exit velocity has remained constant, his fly ball rate has grown from 29% to 41% over the past three seasons. It will be interesting to see how much playing time Milwaukee is willing to give Narvaez behind the plate, where he grades out as a terrible catcher, both as a thrower and a framer. The Mariners were not the contender the Brewers envision themselves being in 2020.

When is adding more loft a bad thing? Shaw was already hitting fly balls at a 45% clip -- a rate more than sufficient to take advantage of Miller Park. However, last season, Shaw adjusted his swing and increased his average launch angle while his fly ball rate soared to 50%. In the process, he almost doubled his strikeout rate fanning 33% of the time. In addition, his fly ball exit velocity fell. The combination harpooned Shaw's average and power as he slashed an anemic .157/.281/.270. The Blue Jays are hoping a reversion to his previous swing buoys a rebound as they have signed Shaw to replace Justin Smoak at first base. Even though it costs next to nothing to see if Shaw can rediscover his power stroke, it's only worth the dart throw in the deepest of formats.

Murphy provides some pop, an increasingly rare trait from a catcher, as well as a level of plate discipline that appeals to fantasy managers across the board. He seemed to sacrifice some of it in the pursuit of greater power around a barrage of injuries, hitting 14 home runs with .290 isolated power in 41 second-half games between the majors and minors. Whether he can maintain those rates is a legitimate question, but he has paths to decent-yet-not-spectacular numbers in batting average and home runs. With more luck in the health department, Murphy could squeak into the top 10 at his position and should be drafted keeping that potential in mind.

Yastrzemski may be no match for his grandfather Carl, but his strong season as a 28-year-old rookie put him on the map as a legitimate big-league talent following a long slog through the minors. He managed 21 homers in 107 games while hitting .272/.334/.518. Statcast bought into his power, giving him an xSLG of .510. While his 26.0 K% and 7.8 BB% were each worse than league average, neither was poor enough to be a serious red flag. Yastrzemski's numbers will continue to be held down this season by a tough home park and a mediocre surrounding lineup, though the Giants' unimpressive roster also means there's less competition for playing time. He didn't play much against lefties last season, but that could change this year after he posted a .943 OPS against them over 89 PA. That would give him even more opportunities to contribute counting stats.

Nothing good lasts forever. That's true even when speaking of Cabrera's dominance. One of the premier hitters of his generation, the future Hall of Famer's numbers have fallen off a cliff as he has progressed through his mid-30s. Sure, Cabrera can still swing the bat -- he hit .285 over the past two seasons -- but his power numbers have taken such a tumble that they're not even league average anymore. In fact, Cabrera's .116 ISO ranked seventh worst among qualified hitters last season, falling squarely between Lorenzo Cain and Hanser Alberto. Injuries certainly bear much of the blame, but given Cabrera's age and body type, he's unlikely to suddenly regain perfect health. The Tigers will continue to reserve a spot in the lineup for the veteran due to his large contract and on-base skills, but his days of being a reliable run producer are long gone.

Under ordinary circumstances, a 30-year-old with 77 games of big-league appearances and a merely decent .273/.344/.410 slash line wouldn't be worth a second look. When that player has stolen 18 bases over that small sample, however, the story is different, especially in a speed-starved era. If Berti were younger, he'd be one of the Marlins' more appealing assets and would likely be able to carve out a significant role for himself this season, but it's just not clear if a veteran his age fits the team's competitive timeline. His ability to play both shortstop and center field goes a long way toward keeping him on the roster in a bench role, but he may not be anything more than that. As long as he plays occasionally, he'll run enough to matter in deep leagues, but his forgettable bat and uncertain role limit his appeal in shallower formats.

Santander spent a fair portion of 2019 in the big leagues and showed good power, hitting 20 homers over 405 PA. The full package wasn't all that impressive, however, as his lopsided .261/.297/.476 slash line was good for a below-average 97 wRC+. That's fine for someone occupying center field, where Santander started 20 games, but the defensive metrics suggest he should probably be limited to the corners. Santander's main weakness at the plate was a 4.7 BB%, though that's a bigger dent to his real-life utility than it is to his fantasy value, outside of OBP leagues. In theory, a young hitter who has shown at least something at the plate and plays in a hitter-friendly home park should make for a fairly safe late-round bet. Beware, though, that Santander doesn't have the pedigree to lock him into an everyday role if his numbers slip.

D'Arnaud was traded to the Rays in mid-May following a brief stint with the Dodgers and went on to experience a surprising renaissance in his age-30 season. He hit .263/.323/.459 with 16 homers in 92 games for his new team, hitting well enough to earn himself 16 starts at first base. The performance was enough to earn him a two-year deal with Atlanta, where his exact playing-time split with Tyler Flowers remains to be seen. D'Arnaud's recent success would seem to give him the advantage, and Statcast gives reason to buy his improvements, giving him an xBA and an xSLG each within four points of his actual numbers. D'Arnaud lacks the track record to push towards the top tier of catchers, but an approximate repeat of last season's showing would be perfectly acceptable.

Based on Cano's 2019 numbers, it's easy to conclude that age is finally catching up to the 15-year veteran, given his durability and performance issues. A closer look suggests that could be only half right, pointing toward a rebound in Cano's age-37 campaign. As to the health concerns, Cano averaged 159 games from 2007 to 2017. In 2018, he would have missed time with a broken pinkie if he hadn't been suspended for 80 games. Last year, he battled through hand, quad and hamstring issues, the latter two resulting in IL stints. Cano is at the age where injuries tend to mount. On the other hand, between the lines, Statcast suggests Cano was just as dangerous as ever, posting an 82nd-percentile average exit velocity and an 87th-percentile hard-hit rate. Even though he fanned a little more, his 16% strikeout rate is still low. There's risk, but it's baked into a big market discount.

Kieboom got off to a tear with Triple-A Fresno to begin 2019, slashing .377/.494/.667 with four homers and 21 RBIs in his first 19 games. Before the end of April he had earned a big-league promotion as Trea Turner's injury fill-in. Kieboom showed some pop in that 11-game audition, but proved otherwise overmatched, after which point he batted .289/.391/.458 with 12 homers in his 90 season-ending games for Fresno. He's expected to be in the Nationals' 3B mix this spring, with several in-season options for playing time across the infield. His top-prospect status and balanced categorical contributions make him an appealing stash even if he fails in his quest to make the Opening Day roster.

Smoak was acquired by Milwaukee in the offseason to improve the team's depth at the first-base position. The switch-hitter does all of his power damage from the left side yet hits for a better average from the right, but neither skill is going to earn him starts on an everyday basis with Ryan Braun likely playing some first to keep his bat in the lineup. The best path forward for Smoak's playing time is an injury to an outfielder (which would force Braun back into an OF-only role), but he will at least see plenty of action as the DH against righties in interleague play. As things look on paper, it will be tough for Smoak to accumulate a significant number of plate appearances in 2020, which will be an unfortunate waste of his ability to hit the ball with authority. He should have signed with a non-contending AL team.

The Mariners signed White to a six-year, $24 million contract in November, before he had ever even appeared in the majors, a sure sign that the team regards him the favorite for their Opening Day first base duties. By all scouts' accounts, his glove is clearly ready for it, and he did turn in a .293/.350/.488 slash line and 18 home runs in 92 games for Double-A Arkansas that gives hope he can contribute some with the bat. Make no mistake: White is regarded more of a line-drive than raw-power type, and it's unclear how quickly he'll be able to generate the contact and extra-base ability points-league managers require from a corner infielder. He's more of a dart throw in mixed leagues, and more so in rotisserie, than someone in whom to fully invest.

Happ failed to earn a roster spot out of spring training and got off to a slow start at Triple-A Iowa, hitting .209 with 25 strikeouts through his first 18 games of 2019. He finally got going and earned a call-up to Chicago shortly after the All-Star break. Happ appeared in 58 games down the stretch, but only 39 of those were starts, split between the outfield, second base, third and first. He's OF-only in leagues with a 20-game minimum. In his limited run with the big club (156 PA), Happ slugged .564 with a much-improved 25.0 K%. He also graded out better on defense. It was a good showing after a disappointing 2018, but it will assure him nothing in 2020. Happ will need to fare well in spring training and impress new manager David Ross to secure a spot in the Opening Day lineup.

O'Neill failed to build on his promising rookie season last year, appearing in one fewer game (60) than he played in 2018. A pair of trips to the injured list were partially to blame, but he also didn't do enough while healthy to carve out a larger role, hitting .262/.311/.411 (good for just a 91 wRC+) with a 35.1 K%. That strikeout rate works for a batter with Joey Gallo-level power, but O'Neill doesn't seem to have that despite his impressive biceps. Neither his 37.2% hard-hit rate nor his 89.2 mph exit velocity would have ranked in the top 100 among qualified batters. Still just 24, there's certainly still a chance he figures out how to make more contact and tap into more power, but a future as a bench bat looms, especially with highly-rated prospect Dylan Carlson knocking on the door.

Formerly a fairly interesting prospect, Smith's career appeared to be at an impasse last offseason after a pair of small-sample failures and the emergence of Pete Alonso. Smith rose to the challenge, however, making the Opening Day roster and hitting .282/.355/.525 with 11 homers over 197 PA before missing most of the second half with a broken foot. That's an encouraging sample, though it's still a small one, and Statcast doesn't fully buy in, giving him an xBA of .246 and an xSLG of .445. Additionally, his defensive work in the outfield -- where he played primarily last season -- graded out poorly. Put it all together and Smith probably fits best as a bench bat. If injuries or a trade to a team that doesn't employ Alonso opens up more playing time, Smith's bat is good enough to merit consideration, but he's not worth much in his current situation.

Choi was quite valuable last season and even helped lift some deep-league owners to championships with six homers and 14 RBIs in September, but the already-crowded Tampa Bay roster is now a full-fledged logjam. The Rays added Yoshi Tsutsugo and Jose Martinez this winter, and they still have former top prospect Nate Lowe, Brandon Lowe and Yandy Diaz, all of whom can play Choi's position at first base. Choi hit just .210/.309/.321 against left-handed pitching, and given what is known about the Rays' tendencies and roster construction, it seems safe to say Choi will almost exclusively be used against righties. Strict platoon players are passable in some mixed-league formats, but the platoon role puts a cap on his upside. The risk of decreased at-bats against right-handers exists if Choi gets off to a slow start or one of his teammates lights the world on fire.

The Mets and Cespedes came to an agreement on a contract restructuring during the offseason, in the hopes of putting behind them the outfielder's injury woes which included, most notably, his fracturing his ankle on an incident at his ranch which inspired several wild stories. He'll not only be trying to prove his health during spring training, but also that he's capable of locking down a regular spot with the Mets, two significant hurdles to clear. That the Mets have a designated hitter spot in which to stash him, however, does boost his appeal as an NL-only late rounder.

On May 31, Bradley's batting average sat at .194. A solid month of June, during which he hit .315 inspired hope of a dramatic turnaround, but his average fell below the Mendoza Line each of the following two months and ultimately settled at .225 by the end of the campaign. That isn't far from his career .236 mark, solidifying Bradley's reputation as a batting-average drain. The veteran's primary problem is making contact. In 2019, he registered a 69.4% contact rate and 27.3% strikeout rate, each among the worst marks in the league. Bradley did notch a solid 9.9 BB%, but that's hardly enough to make up for his contact issues, especially because he did not approach the 17 steals he posted in 2018. Bradley will continue to be a star on defense, but the sample size is large enough to set low expectations regarding his contributions at the plate.

Bader's defensive prowess has kept him in the lineup on a regular basis, but his bat has yet to develop. In 406 PA last season he hit .205/.314/.366 with a 28.8 K%, far too high a rate for a player without any real power. A .268 BABIP held his numbers down somewhat, but it's hard to hit for a high average when you just don't hit the ball very hard, and Statcast gave him an xBA of .219. The Cardinals figure to give him enough at-bats to matter in deeper formats, at least early on, and the speed is there for him to steal double-digit bases. If his bat does not come along, however, Dexter Fowler, Lane Thomas or Dylan Carlson could take over in center field and send Bader to the bench.

Once a poster child for no-hit, all-field shortstops, Ahmed made great strides during the past two seasons to bring his hitting up to a respectable level. In 2019, he enjoyed his best season at the plate, as his .257 xBA, .422 xSLG and 92 wRC+ were all career highs. Ahmed chipped in just enough counting stats -- 19 home runs, 82 RBIs and eight stolen bases -- to appear on the radar in mixed leagues for the first time. Per his career norm, the right-hander struggled against same-handed pitchers (.234 average), but he otherwise didn't do anything particularly poorly. Both his strikeout rate (18.1%) and contact rate (79.8%) were slightly better than league average, and his 8.3 BB% was the best of his career. Ahmed's calling card will always be his defense, but a similar or even better showing at the plate should make him rosterable in most fantasy leagues.

The power surge story of 2019's final two months, Aquino set all sorts of debut season records, most notably matching Rhys Hoskins' record for the most dingers in a player's first 30 contests (14).
