That he calls one of the friendlier offensive environments his home, and that he should be a regular in one of the game's most improved offenses from the offseason, will only help inflate his perceived draft stock. However, Aquino batted just .196/.236/.382 with a 30.9% strikeout rate in his last 27 September games, as opposing pitchers began exploiting the holes in his swing. Regression could hit this sophomore hard in 2020, with streakiness due to his strikeouts the biggest concern. Don't reach for him as anything more than a No. 4 OF in mixed rotisserie leagues, and be aware that his skills are more of a borderline pick in mixed points leagues.

Acquired in the deadline deal for Drew Pomeranz, Dubon earned a five-week, season-ending audition with the Giants, for whom he started 28 of 30 games while posting a .279 batting average fueled by an 81.7% contact rate. Those weren't a far cry from his .300/85.9% career minor league rates, traits that make him a high-floor prospect even if he's lacking in patience, has slowed on the base paths after 2018 ACL surgery and probably isn't the 24-homer performer he was bettern the majors and minors in 2019. Dubon is the kind of safe middle infield pick NL-only managers should appreciate as a fallback, but he'd need to make some sort of significant adjustment to register on the mixed-league radar.

What Frazier lacks in explosiveness he makes up for with consistency. In each of the past three seasons, he hit between .276 and .278 while posting single-digit walk rates and strikeout rates in the mid-teens. He also slugged exactly 10 home runs in each of the past two campaigns and did so in over 250 fewer plate appearances in 2018. Frazier doesn't hit the ball very hard, but he has managed to sustain a useful batting average due to a superb contact rate that grew to a career-best 86.5% last season. While he consistently racked up double-digit stolen-base totals in the minors, Frazier's sprint speed is merely average, and he has yet to swipe more than nine bases in a season in the majors. That detracts from his fantasy value considerably, as he doesn't do enough in any particular category to make him rosterable in most mixed leagues.

Coming off a .292/.372/.542, 26 homer, 20 steal season in 126 games combined between Double-A Springfield and Triple-A Memphis, Carlson should contend for the Cardinals' starting right field role during spring training. His breakthrough was seemingly yet another launch-angle project, trading some contact for pop, albeit not enough to threaten his batting average dropping into the danger zone. Keep an eye on Carlson throughout spring training, as his emergence as an Opening Day starter would thrust him directly into the late-round mix in rotisserie leagues, and thanks to his double-digit annual walk rates he'd be even more attractive in points-based formats.

Standing 5-foot-9, 185 pounds, Fletcher has a short, whippy swing and puts bat to ball with exceptional consistency. His 3.2% swinging-strike rate was the lowest among qualified hitters last season. He rarely expands his small strike zone, and as one would expect of a player with a 10.2 K% in 234 career games, Fletcher has hit for a high average in the big leagues (.285). That average has been rather empty and severely lacking in terms of power, but Fletcher did fill up the runs column last season while leading off in 81 games, and his eight steals were nothing to sneeze at. The dearth of home runs makes him tough to roster in 12-team mixed leagues in this extreme-power era, even with four-position eligibility. His utility in 15-teamers will depend in large part on how often he sits atop the batting order under new manager Joe Maddon.

A power bat with patience who comes with defensive questions, Tsutsugo signed with the Rays after four consecutive seasons in Japan with at least 24 doubles, 28 home runs, a .388 OBP and a .511 slugging percentage. This should appeal especially to those of you in points-based leagues. The team plans to test him at third base and in left field in addition to DH, with third base (a position scouts don't feel he's up to on a regular basis ) being the clearest on the roster. However, on this mix-and-match squad, there should be plenty of opportunities for the lefty hitter nevertheless. If Tsutsugo seems to be adapting to U.S. pitching quickly in the spring, he'll elevate his draft stock to a late-round pick even in ESPN standard leagues. At the onset, he's surely a mid-to-late AL-only pick.

Finally granted a piece of a timeshare following his first-week trade to the Mariners, Murphy flashed the power potential we'd all awaited for years. His 6.4% HR rate and .262 ISO were both fourth-best among catcher-eligibles. He also performed better than expected behind the plate, locking him into at least that role entering 2020. Murphy's history of 30%-plus strikeouts threaten to drag down his batting average and make him streaky, but there's enough pop in his bat to warrant a selection as a No. 2 catcher in mixed leagues.

Thames saw 62 PA against lefties in 2019, which is likely 50 more than he will see against them as a member of the Nationals in 2020. Thames will likely serve as the primary first baseman for the Nationals, but Howie Kendrick and Yan Gomes figure to take on the at-bats against lefties. Thames has the on-base abilities to hit in the upper half of a batting order, which makes him a very intriguing play, even with the limited playing time. Back-to-back seasons of strikeout rates over 30 percent temper the excitement of Thames taking things to another level, as that amount of swinging and missing may make it tough for Davey Martinez to leave Thames up in the lineup on a consistent basis. A drop lower in the lineup should facilitate a drop from your roster, even with plenty of runners likely getting on base in front of him.

Mejia received his first extended look in the majors in 2019, continuing to flash the elevated launch angle he adopted since his mid-2018 trade to the Padres. While it didn't result in big power numbers, he did finish the year with .305/.355/.511 rates in 46 second-half games, those somewhat inflated by a .358 BABIP but still notable considering the dearth of quality catchers in fantasy these days. He'll enter spring training competing for the lion's share of the team's catching chores, with his shaky defense behind the plate his primary obstacle. It's best to project a 50/50 share with Austin Hedges, but even in that limited time Mejia should provide enough to be a worthy mixed-league No. 2 backstop.

Another of the Yankees' fill-in success stories in what was an injury-plagued season for the 2019 squad, Tauchman rode a small rise in his launch angle and a second-half starting opportunity to a .315/.396/.566 slash line, eight home runs, 29 RBIs and five stolen bases while starting 42 of 50 Yankees games between July 18 and Sept. 8, before he, too, had his season cut short on the latter date due to a calf strain. Thanks in large part to his good defense and the Yankees outfielders' injury histories, Tauchman should again make the Opening Day roster, with the chance he could steal some time if bad luck strikes the roster again. A repeat seems unlikely, considering his hard-contact rate was so-so, but he has enough pop, smarts on the base paths and patience to be a helpful AL-only late-rounder or plug-in for mixed league managers.

Heyward experienced a power resurgence last season, posting his most home runs (21) and highest ISO (.177) since 2012. Neither his average launch angle nor average exit velocity saw significant jumps, but Heyward succeeded in hitting a greater number of well-struck balls, as his 5.9% barrel rate more than doubled his mark from the previous campaign. The increased focus on power took a toll on the left-hander's strikeout rate (18.7%, his highest in seven seasons) and batting average (.251, down 19 points from 2018), but the tradeoff was positive in light of Heyward's increased run production. That said, it's highly unlikely that the 30-year-old is primed for a late-career venture into elite power territory, and Heyward's reduced stolen-base totals -- he hasn't reached double-digit thefts since 2016 -- lessen his luster considerably. In mixed leagues, there are better gambles to take with your last bench spot.

Piscotty's numbers were limited by injury for the second time in three seasons. He struggled with two major lower-half injuries (knee, ankle), which clearly impacted his ability to maintain the power gains he showcased in 2018. Part of his breakout season in 2018 was tied to him handling righties extremely well compared to other full seasons. His .841 OPS against righties in 2018 was nearly 100 points better than that of any previous season, and the 220-point fall last year was part of his overall statistical demise. Oakland does not have a clear platoon partner for Piscotty, so the full-time job will likely remain his, but if he does not get back to at least league average against righties, his overall numbers will continue to underwhelm.

One of the top power prospects in baseball -- he has career .220 isolated power as a pro and routinely draws 70 grades or better in scouts' 80-grade system -- Adell certainly didn't show it in 27 games for Triple-A Salt Lake in 2019, going homerless with a 47% ground ball rate there. He'll probably return there to begin the year, but could move quickly with a similarly strong output to the .308/.390/.553 he slashed in Double-A to begin last season. Adell is one of the top dynasty league prospects to stash, and in redraft leagues, he's well worth a speculative pick on the hopes of a midseason callup, should your league afford you the requisite bench space or minor league spots.

Fowler had nowhere to go but up after a disastrous 2018 campaign during which he registered a .180 BA and 63 wRC+. The veteran did improve last season, though his .238 BA was hardly reason to celebrate. Fowler's poor hitting was rooted in his declining contact skills, as his 75.2% contact rate and 24.7 K% were each the worst marks of his career. When he did hit the ball, Fowler generated a meager 85.2 mph average exit velocity, placing him in the bottom 10th percentile league wide. With that in mind, it's irrational to expect him to repeat last season's career-best mark of 19 home runs. Fowler deserves some credit for finding other ways to reach base -- he was hit by a pitch eight times and notched a solid 12.9 BB% -- but that's not enough to make him fantasy-viable, especially in light of his declining stolen-base numbers.

Jansen flopped in his first full season in the big leagues. In his first audition with the Blue Jays in 2018 (95 PA), Jansen hit .247/.347/.432 with three homers and a 17.9 K%, good for a 116 wRC+. He did not come close to matching those rate numbers in 2019, providing a lesson against small-sample optimism. Statcast says Jansen deserved better -- his xBA was .247 -- and keep in mind he was only 24 years old for most of last season. That being said, Jansen lost the playing-time edge to Reese McGuire in September and his extreme pull tendencies will lead to more teams shifting against him, likely capping his BA. Jansen saw a traditional shift against him in 117 of his PA last year and hit .197 in those situations. He will need to compete to earn the primary catcher role back in spring training.

They are moving in the outfield walls at Oracle Park this season, but that may not be enough to salvage Longoria's fantasy value. His second season in San Francisco was a significant improvement on his first, from a real-world perspective, as Longoria raised his walk rate to 8.5% -- his highest mark since 2013. His defense at third base also rebounded. However, his fantasy utility did not match up. Longoria failed to crack even 130 runs-plus-RBI despite hitting mostly 3-5 in the order, and while that is not really "his fault," the team around him isn't any better entering 2020. His rate/power numbers are barely above league average, and he plays a position ripe with power hitters. Longoria has cleared 500 PA in seven consecutive seasons, providing a safe floor that is appealing in NL-only leagues. However, late in mixed-league drafts, most will want to chase upside instead.

Urias was looking awfully intriguing following his offseason trade to the Brewers and into their hitting-friendly home ballpark, not to mention where he was projected to play shortstop and add that in-season eligibility, until he hurt his wrist during winter ball in Mexico and succumbed to January surgery that now threatens his Opening Day status. It's best to assume at least a short IL stint, which casts a cloud on his role upon activation, problematic especially when coupled with his pro-worst 22.5% strikeout rate in the majors in 2019. Urias is mostly a stash for now, though he's a more intriguing prospect in dynasty leagues.

Perez rewarded the Indians for entrusting him with a regular role, obliterating his personal bests across the board while winning the American League Gold Glove. The defensive wizardry may not count in fantasy, but it will help Perez remain the bell cow if his newfound batting prowess wanes. To wit, heading into the season, he clubbed a meager 21 homers in 963 career trips to the dish. In 2019, he slammed 24 in 449 plate appearances. He'll be hard-pressed to match that total, considering a likely regression to his 28% HR/FB mark, in concert with a 50% ground ball clip, but with volume now part of his profile, Perez should clear the fence enough to remain a fantasy asset despite a low batting average.

Picked up from the Yankees in a January 2019 trade, Long earned a brief look with the Mariners in May/June while Dee Gordon was sidelined by injury, followed by a more extended audition shuffling between second base and left field in September, during which time he batted .289/.337/.518 with four homers in 23 games. He'll get a long look this spring, with second base the more likely destination. A victory in said battle would put him on the (deeper) mixed-league middle-infield radar.

Castro played in only 79 games last season while occupying the No. 2 spot on the Twins' catching depth chart behind Mitch Garver. He struck out in 32% of his plate appearances but supplied the second-best SLG of his career (while also walking at a healthy clip), leading to a 103 wRC+. Behind the plate, Castro grades out as a significant plus, although his pop times and framing are just OK by Statcast measures. He missed most of the 2018 season after undergoing surgery to repair a torn meniscus in his right knee, but after signing Castro to a one-year, $6.85 million deal, the Angels are hoping he can clear 100 games played in 2020 . He's a batting-average liability, but Castro cracked double-digit homers in six of the last seven seasons. He should do so again with Angels Stadium playing friendlier for lefty power since the boundary in right field was lowered.

Gonzalez's 2017 stands out as the clear outlier when looking at a statistical snapshot of his last six seasons. That season, Gonzalez hit .303 with 23 home runs and a 144 wRC+. His wRC+ ranged from 89 to 111 in the five seasons surrounding 2017. So, essentially Gonzalez is a league-average bat -- slightly above league average when things are going well -- with his calling card being his ability to play all around the diamond. His time in the middle infield was limited in his first season with the Twins and he has lost second-base and shortstop eligibility entering 2020. Gonzalez maintains eligibility in the outfield and at both corner-infield positions. For a while this winter, Gonzalez sat atop the depth chart at first base by default, but he was always likely to remain in his super-utility role. After the team signed Josh Donaldson, Miguel Sano is now slotted in at first.

Franco followed a promising second half of the 2018 campaign with a dud in 2019. His home run output dipped into the teens for the first time in four seasons, and his 70 wRC+ ranked seventh-worst in the league among players with at least 400 PA. Furthermore, Franco's batting average tumbled 36 points to a paltry .234. At first glance, that number seems surprising from a hitter who posted a superb 84.3% contact rate and struck out only 14.3% of the time. However, the low number becomes perfectly rational when considering the 24.1% infield fly ball rate that ranked dead last in the majors -- by more than four percent -- and led to a scant .236 BABIP. Franco will attempt to resurrect his career in Kansas City after signing with the Royals in the offseason, but his body of work to date inspires little confidence in his fantasy viability.

After batting .213, .213 and .225 in the previous three seasons, Frazier turned a few fly balls into line drives spurring a .251 average for 2019. While his power wasn't the same as in his salad days, Frazier hit over 20 homers for the fifth time in six years. Bogged down with 20th-percentile spring speed, Frazier only stole one bag -- noteworthy since sneaky steals used to be an integral aspect of his fantasy contributions. The 34-year old veteran signed with Texas where he'll compete for playing time at both corner infield spots. The move from Citi Field should help Frazier maintain last season's output, though the new Rangers venue isn't expected to play nearly as hitter-friendly as the old one. Frazier is in play in AL-only formats, but likely won't play enough for mixed-league consideration.

The favorite for the Tigers' starting catcher role entering 2020, Romine delivered quality defense and middling pop when pushed into regular duty by Gary Sanchez's injuries with the Yankees over the past two seasons. This should carry over to his new team. Romine lacks the contact ability needed to hit for a high average and his power isn't close to equaling Sanchez's -- and it's possible that a .270-15 stat line is his 2020 ceiling. Considering the catching pool these days, though, that's probably enough to warrant No. 2 mixed-league status.

Long one of the premier base stealers in baseball, Gordon disappointed last season, ranking outside the top 10 in stolen bases for the first time since 2013. That was largely due to a slew of injuries that limited the speedster to just 117 games, his lowest total in three years. Still, Gordon stole fewer bases (22) than he did in his 79-game season in 2016, so injuries weren't solely to blame. After spending the vast majority of his career in the leadoff position (and despite a paltry 4.1 BB%), Gordon logged 79% of his plate appearances in the bottom third of the order last season, resulting in fewer steal attempts when he did reach base. The 31-year-old did hit .331 in 178 at-bats from the No. 9 spot and should continue to be a stolen-base asset, but don't expect him to get anywhere close to the 60-theft mark that was once his norm.

One of the stories of the 2019 season was the emergence of several back-end catchers. Unfortunately, Barnhart was not one of them, posting an 81 wRC+, which was 22nd among catchers with at least 300 plate appearances. Barnhart's .231 average was his lowest since becoming Cincinnati's primary backstop in 2016. A 12th-percentile average exit velocity working in tandem with a career-worst 22.8% strikeout rate were the culprits. While the Reds improved their position players, they didn't address the catcher position, as they likely expect highly regarded prospect Tyler Stephenson to debut sometime this season. Barnhart should be ignored in single-catcher formats.

Last year was another season of the "same old" Moreland. He started mostly against right-handed pitching (eight starts vs. LHP) and was a little bit better than league average. Moreland struck out 22.1% of the time while walking at a 10.1% clip -- nearly identical to his 2018 marks. He just could not push past 400 plate appearances again because a right quad strain wiped out a significant chunk of his season. A free agent this winter, Moreland eventually re-upped with the Red Sox on a one-year, $3 million deal. There is nothing exciting about Moreland, now 34, but he's a strong bet to hit 20 home runs if he can stay healthy and remain on the strong side of a platoon all year. The deeper the league, the more appeal Moreland has. Most in mixed leagues will want to chase upside instead, as the type of production Moreland provides is fairly easy to replace in shallower formats.

Galvis is an above-average defender at shortstop and should be the Reds' Opening Day starter at the position. He has an impatient approach at the plate, leading to few walks and a high strikeout rate thus holding down his batting average and on-base percentages. He does possess decent pop, particularly from the left side, and showcased that last year in Toronto before a late season deal-to Cincinnati. Great American Ballpark presents him with an opportunity to hit 20 homers again if he can stay in the lineup enough. The expected stats are not optimistic about a step forward, but over the past four seasons, Galvis was a productive compiler of counting stats. The glove should keep him in the lineup regularly, and he figures to occupy a spot lower in the batting order.

After receiving only sporadic playing time over the previous three campaigns, Vogelbach seized hold of the available opportunities on the rebuilding Mariners last season, finishing the year with a lopsided but respectable .208/.341/.439 slash line (111 wRC+) and 30 homers. That low batting average can't be blamed on contact issues, as his 26.7 K% wasn't all that high for a slugger, but instead on his .232 BABIP. If that number gets closer to league average (.298) Vogelbach could produce a respectable batting average to go along with decent power, but his complete lack of speed and his fly-ball profile mean a low BABIP is to be expected. Still, Vogelbach should hit enough homers to offset his low average again this season, and he can now focus exclusively on hitting as the DH with Evan White at first base.

The Cubs' 2018 first-round pick, Hoerner leapt all the way to the majors last September despite only 89 games of minor-league experience -- and only 70 at the Double-A level. Yet, he held his own in his brief audition. He'll be in the spring 2B competition, his knack for contact perhaps giving him a realistic chance at winning the job. In reality, he could probably use additional Triple-A seasoning. Stash Hoerner in deep-mixed and NL-only leagues, and consider him a high-floor performer in the big-league games he gives you.

Mountcastle is a solid, power-oriented prospect, but questions about his defensive position are presumably the final hurdle to clear before he debuts with the Orioles. A potential option at DH, first base, left field or at third base (in that order of likelihood), he might be capable of duplicating 2019's 25 Triple-A homers at the big-league level if given a chance. That said, his free-swinging ways make a .312 batting average (or anything close to it) a longshot. Mountcastle's skills are more appealing in rotisserie than points leagues, so regard him a stronger stash there.

Reyes has elite speed, a plus arm, and the defensive metrics are all favorable. Normally, this isn't relevant for fantasy but with Reyes, it makes him the most likely candidate to man center field in Motown. His patience needs work to hit leadoff, but Reyes makes decent contact with just enough pop to be dangerous. The team context isn't great for run production, but it's more than commensurate with where you'll likely draft the 25-year old outfielder. Reyes can steal bases, running with 91st-percentile sprint speed. In leagues with daily moves, Reyes is ideally deployed on Monday and Thursday, where you'll hope for some steals while one of your regular outfielders has a travel day.

An inner-circle Hall of Famer, Pujols is no longer a big-time threat with the bat as he enters his age-40 season. He's been below the replacement-level threshold by real-world measures for the last three years, hitting between .241-.245 with OBPs between .286-.305. The power is basically league average nowadays and Pujols provides zero value on the defensive side. In fact, he's a negative in the field. To his credit, he did manage to drive in 93 runs last season, tying for 14th in the American League, but it took a .294/.362/.551 line with runners in scoring position to get him there. That's unsustainable and Anthony Rendon may cash in a lot of those baserunners in 2020 while batting behind Mike Trout (but ahead of Pujols) in the batting order. Pujols can be safely left on the waiver wire in most mixed leagues.

Rodgers batted .356/.421/.644 with nine home runs in 35 games to begin his 2019 at Triple-A Albuquerque, earning a promotion to the Rockies in mid-May, taking over for the struggling Garrett Hampson. Rodgers would struggle to the tune of 22 strikeouts and only two extra-base hits in 65 at-bats, perhaps pressing in his first taste of the majors, beforegoing down with a shoulder impingement that eventually required season-ending surgery in July. When healthy, Rodgers has a strong balance of contact ability, pop and speed, equally appealing in both rotisserie and points-based leagues. He could be a dynasty pickup on the cheap.

Even in today's power-driven landscape, there's a place for high-contact, slap hitters if they're slapping line drives and grounders. Peraza's 42.6% fly ball rate was far too high, resulting in easy outs, even in The Great American Bandbox. In addition, Peraza walked only 4.2% of the time, limiting the ability to take advantage of his primary skill, 75th percentile sprint speed. With no place for him in their revamped infield, Cincinnati non-tendered Peraza, freeing him up to sign with the Red Sox, with whom he'll compete for playing time at the keystone. Even if he wins the job, his production won't warrant anything other than end-game attention in AL-only formats.

Bruce opened 2019 with the Mariners, slashing .212/.283/.533 at the end of May when he was dealt to Philadelphia, ostensibly as a reserve. Right after the deal became official, Andrew McCutchen tore his ACL, thrusting Bruce into a starting role. He posted a .221/.235/.510 line for the Phillies, walking just three times in 149 plate appearances. The injury bug also bit Bruce as he missed about six weeks with two IL stints, first for a sore oblique, then a flexor strain. Bruce's extreme fly ball approach was good for power but overall poor plate skills (24.7% K-rate, 5.7% BB-rate) and a .200 BABIP crushed both his average and OBP. Bruce is expected to back up corner outfield and first base, but could factor as the Phillies' designated hitter if McCutchen is prepared to serve as an everyday outfielder. Stay tuned.

Injuries -- a lumbar strain, a hamstring strain and quad issues -- prevented Inciarte from logging even a half-season's worth of at-bats in 2019. He began the year batting leadoff vs. RHP but lost that spot a couple weeks into the season and never reclaimed the table-setter role for Atlanta. His increased pull tendencies continued, and his strikeout rate ticked up to 17.8%, leading to another dip in batting average, which slipped 58 points during the last two years. However, on account of raising his walk rate nearly four percentage points to 11.3%, Inciarte's overall offensive performance stayed within his career norms in OPS and wRC+. His running was limited around the injuries, and he's not assured of a starting role after the team signed Marcell Ozuna. Remember, too, that the Braves have two top outfield prospects (Cristian Pache and Drew Waters) waiting in the wings.

In what amounts to basically a full season of MLB playing time -- split over three calendar years -- Crawford has hit .222 with 10 homers, eight steals and a wRC+ of 88. That's essentially the pace he was on last year in his first season with the Mariners, but he was limited to 93 games by ankle and hamstring injuries. As a plus defensively at shortstop, Crawford was able to provide some real-life value to Seattle, but at this point it's looking like the former top prospect will never hit enough to be relevant outside of AL/NL-only formats. Virtually nothing in the batted-ball profile suggests there's more to come; his average exit velocity and hard-hit rate both ranked in the bottom 6% of the league, and he has totaled 13 barrels (by Statcast's definition) on 399 batted-ball events in the big leagues. He will likely be afforded more time to figure something out on a rebuilding team.

Note the pattern: Diaz struggled in his first taste at both Double-A and Triple-A before eventually excelling at each level. It's possible that his poor 2019 audition with the Marlins provided him the requisite experience to now improve. He had major issues with contact, but continued to show a fly ball-heavy, contact-driven, three-true-outcomes sort of approach. It's one that might result in a sneaky-good number of homers . Remember, the Marlins did move in the RF fences for 2020. Consider him a deep-mixed/NL-only flier, but one with high variance.

One team's trash is another team's treasure. Cabrera hit just .235/.318/.393 over the first four months of 2019 and the Rangers designated him for assignment. Not only were they unable to find a trade partner, but no team was even willing to claim Cabrera off waivers even though he was only making $3.5 million for the entire season. After his unconditional release, Cabrera immediately signed with Washington, and the rest is history. Cabrera hit .323/.404/.565 in 38 games for the Nationals over the remainder of the regular season and went on to hit .286 in the World Series while starting five games. The Nats brought him back after their championship season and will likely slot Cabrera in at third base, with Starlin Castro at second. Cabrera will have third-base and second-base eligibility on draft day and the switch-hitter's floor still looks pretty sturdy.

Hopefully you let someone else shell out for Lopez when he was summoned to the majors last season. While not a marquee prospect, Lopez had real buzz as a minor leaguer and there was some thought that he could steal double-digit bases while hitting for a high average. Some things did translate, with Lopez posting a low 12.7 K% in his 402 plate appearances with Kansas City. Unfortunately, that was the only skill to carry over, as Lopez could not tap into the gap power he showed at Triple-A. He struggled with plate patience, with his BB% falling from 14.5% to just 4.5% after the jump in levels. Worst of all for those who took the chance, Lopez hardly ran at all, swiping just one bag in two attempts with the major-league team. On the plus side, with Whit Merrifield moving to the outfield full time, second base looks it may be Lopez's to lose, at least.

Winker showed decent power for the first time in 2019, though he took enough steps back in other areas that his campaign can't really be considered a breakout. He managed 16 homers over 384 PA after hitting just seven in 334 opportunities the previous year, but his average dropped from .299 to .269, his BB% fell from 14.7 to 9.9 and his K% rose from 13.8 to 15.6. Even the positive development in his power numbers comes with caveats, as his fly ball rate, barrel rate, exit velocity and launch angle all dropped. He's still a decent hitter, but after finishing the year with a lengthy injury-related absence for the second straight season and with new competition for at-bats in the form of Nick Castellanos and Shogo Akiyama, he's a risky bet.

Maybin began last season in the Cleveland minor-league system before landing with New York when injuries hit the Yankees hard. He battled some injuries of his own -- a left calf strain and a left wrist issue -- but performed well when on the field. At 32 years old, Maybin posted an 11.2 BB% and bested his previous career high in ISO by 50 points. His .285 batting average was his second-best mark in a full season, although it took a .365 BABIP to get there. After stealing 33 bases just three seasons ago, Maybin swiped just nine last year, with diminished efficiency (9-for-15). As of late January, Maybin remains unsigned, but the No. 10 overall pick from the 2005 draft showed he can still provide value on a big-league bench and should land a major-league job. The expanded rosters afforded in 2020 helps a fifth-outfielder-type like Maybin stick around.

It's Iglesias' glove that keeps him in a team's lineup regularly, and he's fortunate to have found a new home with the rebuilding Orioles, who can stand to trot him out there for a majority of their games. While he set a professional best with his 11 home runs in 2019, let's remember the context of the homer-happy baseball, as the remainder of his game had the same ordinary look as it did in his five seasons with the Tigers. Iglesias can help an AL-only team thanks to the counting numbers he provides, but he's severely lacking in upside.

After losing the majority of the 2018 season to wrist issues, Cooper broke camp as the Marlins' starting right fielder. Three games into the season he was shelved with a calf issue, returning for just a game before heading back to the IL after being hit in the hand. Cooper was activated in mid-May and avoiding the injury bug until a knee issue shut him down in mid-September. On the field, Cooper posted a 111 wRC+, consistent with a productive minor-league career. His 23.8% HR/FB mark was well above league average, but a low 23% flyball rate and high 26.1% strikeout rate limited production. It's unclear where Cooper will play as Miami brought in several veterans. The most likely spot is sharing first base with Jesus Aguilar, though the right-handed-swinging Cooper fared much better against right-handed pitching last season.

Mitch Haniger's injury opened up the Mariners' right field race to a battle between Fraley, Braden Bishop and others this spring, with Fraley considered the favorite to emerge from the group. He enjoyed a power breakthrough in the upper minors in 2019, hitting 19 homers in 99 games combined between Double- and Triple-A, and added 24 steals to give him additional rotisserie appeal. Track that position battle throughout July, as Fraley would be well worth an AL-only late round pick if he's the victor, and he might even scratch the mixed-league radar in the best case scenario.

A surprisingly-good 2018 gave Hernandez some mixed-league sleeper buzz heading into 2019. Unfortunately, he could not build on his strong campaign and instead took a sizable step backward in his age-27 season. His gains against right-handed pitching were washed away, with Hernandez batting just .221/.285/.403 without the platoon edge (down from .252/.338/.495 vs. RHP in 2018). His strikeout and walk rates both went in the wrong direction by three-plus percentage points while his barrel rate sagged to 5.9%. To his credit, Hernandez remained a plus on defense and provided versatility with his ability to play all around the diamond. However, it is important to note that Hernandez has lost shortstop eligibility entering 2020. Given his decline and the emergence of uber-prospect Gavin Lux at second base, Hernandez appears likely to see a reduction in playing time this season.

A left quad strain suffered during the first week of April put Lamb on the shelf for more than two months. By the time he made it back onto the field, Christian Walker had put his stamp on the first base job and Eduardo Escobar continued to hold down the hot corner. With that, Lamb was relegated to part-time duty -- and that role was scaled back even further in September amidst a prolonged slump. Lamb can take a walk, however, and he hit the ball hard in his limited play last year, not to mention he might be a fit as the Diamondbacks' new designated hitter. Kevin Cron and/or Josh Rojas could also factor into that mix, so be cautious regarding Lamb anything more than a fantasy backup for now.

The Blue Jays traded Kendrys Morales to the Athletics just before opening day, paving the way for Tellez to get regular at-bats at first base and designated hitter. He failed to take advantage and was shipped to Triple-A Buffalo in July. Tellez regained his stroke on the farm and hit an improved, but still pedestrian, 226/.325/.481 down the stretch. Poor plate skills (28.4% K% and 7.1% BB%) hurt Tellez as his 80th percentile average exit velocity and 68th percentile hard-hit rate are acceptable. The Blue Jays have several options at first base and designated hitter, so it will take a strong camp with improved on-base skills for Tellez to carve out a fantasy-friendly role.

While never regarded a blue-chip prospect, Lowe possesses the tools of an intriguing points-league prospect, thanks to his minor league track record of high on-base percentages, decent contact and some pop. He slashed .289/.421/.508 in 93 games for Triple-A Durham, but in a 50-game taste of the majors, only the pop translated. For Lowe to break through, he'll need to recapture that prior patience, and he'll have a harder time doing so on a Rays team that added Jose Martinez and Yoshitomo Tsutsugo to the first base/DH mix. Consider Lowe a deep mixed/AL-only stash, barring a lights-out spring.

So much for O'Hearn building on his 2018 breakthrough and providing cheap power last season. After slugging .597 in 44 games to close out the 2018 campaign, gravity spiraled O'Hearn back to earth last year as he posted a disappointing .195/.281/.369 line, falling into a platoon by season's end. O'Hearn's Statcast measurables were down last season but, to be fair, that's not enough to account for the precipitous drop in performance. This suggests a combination of good luck in 2018 and bad luck last season. The acquisition of Maikel Franco frees up Hunter Dozier to move across the diamond. However, Dozier can also move to corner outfield, so O'Hearn needs a strong spring to return to his platoon playing time. Regardless, there are better options in mixed leagues.

Haseley's patience and solid contact skills in the minors earned him a look as a near-regular all over the Phillies outfield during the second half of 2019, and while those skills didn't seem to translate in the majors, perhaps his relative inexperience in the upper minors simply means he needed more time to adjust. He provided solid defense, which is probably the basis for his entering spring training the favorite for center field duties (at least against righties), though a good Grapefruit League campaign would be needed before he's anything more than NL-only material.

Performance variance is discussed a lot in reference to a pitcher, but batters are subject to under- and over-performing their peripherals as well. While Camargo's underlying metrics did slip a bit last season, it wasn't nearly enough to account for the slide in overall numbers. To wit, in 2018, his wOBA was .346, well over his .310 Statcast expected mark. Last season, his expected wOBA was .282, lower than the previous season, but he posted an actual .279, in line with Statcast's estimation. The message is he was lucky in 2018, with the logical baseline in line with 2019. Unfortunately, that's not fantasy-friendly production, and Camargo would need to emerge as a regular at third base to be relevant in deeper leagues.

Tapia got a long look in the majors last season, compiling 447 plate appearances over 138 games. He's never going to be much of a power hitter, so his nine home runs were in line with expectations, but his .275 batting average was slightly disappointing, considering the Coors Field factor and his career .319 minor-league mark. Tapia's nine stolen bases were also a mild disappointment, as he possesses excellent speed and has swiped as many as 33 bags in a minor-league season. To take advantage of his speed, Tapia would be well-served to reach base by any means, but he has thus far showed an aversion to taking walks, and he registered a paltry 4.7 BB% last season. Tapia has the skills to be an above-average hitter and contribute in the increasingly elusive stolen-base department, but a crowded outfield may block his path to a starting role in 2020.

A return to the 30-SB plateau for Dyson in 2019 was fueled in part by his amassing a professional-best 452 plate appearances. The boost in playing time helped alleviate any concerns about declining speed as he approaches this, his age-35, season. After all, his new deal with the Pirates probably assures him a similarly large role as their center fielder. Dyson is unfortunately a one-trick pony, there in the late rounds as a mere safety net if you left your team light on stolen bases. In points-based leagues, you can freely move on.

Kipnis rebounded slightly last season, as his .245 BA and 26.9 AB/HR were his best marks since 2016. Still, neither stat jumps off the page, and the two-time All-Star finished with an 82 wRC+ that ranked third worst among qualified second basemen. Kipnis still makes good contact -- he posted an 80.8% contact rate last season -- but his tendency to put the ball in the air (41.2 FB%), coupled with a below-average 5.5% barrel rate and a mediocre 86.7 mph average exit velocity, led to frequent outs. Kipnis was a lock for 20-plus stolen bases earlier in his career, but he has not reached double digits in that category since 2016, further limiting his fantasy value. He'll get a fresh start playing somewhere other than Cleveland for the first time in 2020, but there's no guarantee he will have an everyday role.

It looked like Goodwin was set to retreat to a bench role when the Angels had a deal in place to acquire Joc Pederson. That trade fell through, however, so Goodwin remains atop the depth chart in right field -- for now. Goodwin quietly had a pretty nice year in 2019, hitting 17 homers while stealing seven bases, but he's a soon-to-be 30-year-old with a career .255/.320/.461 line at the big-league level. That's perfectly fine for a reserve outfielder, but not for a starting corner outfielder on a contending team, which is what the Angels fancy themselves in 2020. Top prospect Jo Adell looms as a threat to take Goodwin's job, possibly as soon as late April. Goodwin would probably need another long-term Justin Upton injury to remain relevant throughout the year. However, as a reserve, he should fall into enough playing time to be useful in AL-only leagues.

Haniger's health is a big question mark heading into 2020. He suffered a freak injury last year when he fouled a ball off his groin, rupturing a testicle. While rehabbing, Haniger's back became sore, he did not respond well to treatment, and the Mariners eventually gave up hope for a September return. In late September, it was reported that Haniger would not have any restrictions this spring, but Haniger was ultimately forced to undergo hernia surgery in late January. It was estimated that he'd need 6-to-8 weeks to recover, though GM Jerry Dipoto would not commit to that timetable. With Opening Day in doubt, and after a significant strikeout rate spike in his age-28 season to 28.6%, Haniger is a true wild card. In mixed leagues without IL spots, he's borderline. At least we know he'll play when (if?) he gets healthy.

A hot start with Triple-A Tacoma (.327/.415/.520) earned Nola his first big-league call-up in June at the age of 29. He ended up faring quite well at the plate with Seattle in his 79 games split between first base, second, third, catcher and the outfield, cracking 10 homers and posting a 114 wRC+ over 267 PA. Unfortunately, only seven of his appearances came behind the plate, so Nola has lost catcher eligibility in most fantasy leagues heading into 2020. If he had maintained C-eligibility, or if he were to regain it in-season, Nola could return to relevance, as he would project to play just enough in his utility role to be useful at a thin position. He's not really viable anywhere else in a starting fantasy lineup. Nola had never slugged even .400 at any stop in the minors before last year and Statcast says he was out over his skis in the majors, given the batted-ball numbers.

Lewis stroked 17 home runs between the majors and minors last season, surrendering contact for power in order to earn his late-season promotion from Double-A. He has long been considered a good-not-great prospect with decent pop, but the warning signs were evident: .351 BABIP with his 38.7% big-league strikeout rate hinting huge batting average downside, and mediocre-at-best ground ball and hard-contact rates. Lewis has some adjustments to make while he battles for a starting outfield spot in the spring, and he's mostly a final-round dart throw or dynasty mid-to-late rounder for now.

This will be Gordon's 15th season, and it may very well be his last. He admitted last September he was pondering retirement but ultimately re-upped with the Royals on a one-year deal. At age 35, Gordon cut his strikeout rate to a career-low 15.8% after it got as high as 29.2% a few seasons back. He also maintained a respectable walk rate and raised his OBP to .345 -- his highest mark since 2015. However, he hit just .266 even with all that contact, and given his middling batted-ball numbers, there's likely only one direction for that average to go this season. His decline in speed as he's pushed into his mid-30s has hurt in that regard -- Gordon's BABIP did not top .301 in the last four years -- as well as in regard to his value on the basepaths (5-for-8 on SB attempts in 2018). There is not a shred of upside here and the floor could drop out.

Guzman had a chance to seize the first base job in Texas last season but hit the injured list with a hamstring strain early in the campaign, struggled to get going following his return and was eventually optioned to Triple-A for more than a month. He returned in September and hit .305, but 22 strikeouts in 68 plate appearances during that span should temper enthusiasm. His overall numbers without the platoon edge were ugly (.536 OPS), and while Guzman is still relatively young at 25, it does not seem the Rangers are optimistic about Guzman finding another level to his game. They brought in Todd Frazier on a one-year deal, and Frazier projects to see a good amount of time at first base, with Nick Solak playing some at third. With that, Guzman loses whatever appeal he had outside of AL-only leagues.

An old-school leadoff man, Garcia showed decent speed (15 steals) and a respectable batting average (.279) last season but posted a paltry 3.4 BB% and a poor 83 wRC+. While his role allowed him to provide fantasy owners 93 runs in 2019, don't expect a repeat of that this year. The retooled White Sox look to be pushing for a playoff spot and likely don't want a bat as weak as Garcia's hitting atop the order. It's quite likely Garcia loses his starting role altogether, as highly-touted center-field prospect Luis Robert signed an extension in January, presumably paving the way for him to occupy a spot in the Opening Day lineup. Garcia's ability to play both center field and shortstop should keep him around in a bench capacity, but he won't do much other than provide the occasional steal if injuries open up extra playing time.

Flores signed with the Diamondbacks last offseason, expected to fortify the right side of the infield as early onset arthritis in both knees has limited what he can do defensively. Flores wasn't limited at the plate, as he set new career bests in average and on-base percentage, falling .001 points short of tying his personal high slugging percentage. A 5% shift from fly balls to line drives buoyed Flores' average, while the 2019 fun ball helped keep the power afloat in light of reduced fly balls. Now with the Giants, expect Flores to revert to previous performance levels in a less-hitter-friendly venue, though he has a chance to surpass last season's 89 games and 265 plate appearances.

Zunino has always fanned a ton, but last season his power cratered to the point he lost the regular gig to Travis d'Arnaud. Zunino's contact actually improved a couple points, but a drop in average exit velocity and more fly balls doesn't sync up with the cavernous space in Tropicana Field. Still, after swatting 45 homers from 2017-2018, Zunino deserves a little benefit of the doubt. A power return is likely and, with d'Arnaud gone, Zunino should regain the starting job. The middle portion of the catcher ranks has improved, but the back end remains dreadful. As such, Zunino will find his way onto some fantasy rosters in two-catcher leagues, hopefully with plenty of batting-average buffer.

A candidate for a corner-outfield spot -- or at least a share of a platoon -- with the Tigers this spring, Stewart possesses big-time power potential yet showed little of it in his first extended taste of the majors in 2019 (10 homers, .154 isolated power in 416 trips to the plate). His swing has the necessary loft, but until he generates more consistently hard contact, and frankly contact at all, he'll be a shaky fantasy option in all but AL-only leagues that afford you daily transactions.

Normally, there's a question whether power will suffer after shoulder surgery. When the recipient is a 34-year-old catcher, it's basically assumed home runs will wane. Just the opposite occurred with Vogt, as he crushed his career bests in ISO and slugging percentage, playing half his games in Oracle Park, no less. A modest increase in fly balls along with a marked leap in average exit velocity did the trick. Vogt parlayed his rejuvenated season into a one-year deal with the Diamondbacks , with whom he'll serve as Carson Kelly's understudy. Beware, Kelly is maturing at the dish and in the field, so Vogt is likely to fall short of last season's 280 plate appearances, relegating him to fantasy status only in deep two-catcher formats.

Souza's 2019 season ended before it could begin, as he slipped on home plate during the Diamondbacks' final exhibition game and he ended up with tears to his ACL, LCL, PCL and posterior lateral capsule. After the lost season, Arizona declined to tender Souza a contract for 2020, making him a free agent. In December, reports surfaced saying Souza had been hitting, running and throwing at 100 percent. A little over a month later, Souza finalized a one-year, major-league deal with the Cubs. As the roster stands, Souza appears to be on the outside looking, but he's best suited for short-side platoon duty anyway. He has been below league average by wRC+ in three of his five seasons, and has been significantly above league average only once (121 wRC+ in 2017). Souza's K-rate has routinely sat around 30% and he has a .229/.317/.417 career line against right-handed pitching.

Despite a strong spring, Sisco opened the 2019 season with Triple-A Norfolk, slashing a productive .292/.388/.550 before being promoted in June. Sisco shared catching duties with Pedro Severino the rest of the way, posting a weak .210/.333/.395. He appeared to be overmatched at the plate with a 31% strikeout rate. Sisco and Severino will again share playing time, with the latter likely earning more action. The truth is, both are battling for the right to be the future backup to last year's top overall draft pick, Adley Rutschman, perhaps as early as 2021.

Flowers will return to the Braves where he'll back up Travis d'Arnaud behind the dish. However, with d'Arnaud's injury history, Flowers could end up matching the 300-or-so plate appearances he's compiled both of the last two seasons. After a couple of productive years with Atlanta from 2016-2017, Flowers has reverted to his previous form of late, flashing a little power in-between strikeouts. He's an above-average receiver who could help the maturing Braves pitching staff. One-catcher formats need not apply, but Flowers is in play in deep two-catcher leagues where you're able to absorb a batting-average drain to add some pop and run production.

Sogard began the season with Triple-A Buffalo but was called up by the Blue Jays in mid-April. After floundering the previous year with Milwaukee, Sogard reverted to his 2018 form, resulting in a deadline deal to the Rays. By season's end, Sogard shattered his career high in homers while also setting a new personal-best in slugging percentage. His exit velocity on fly balls and average fly ball distance were both well below the league average, but his spray chart shows that Sogard hit almost all his homers down the line where the fence is closer. He should benefit from returning to Miller Park, though there's no guarantee he'll be fortunate enough to pull so many fly balls. He is 2B-eligible to start the 2020 campaign, but Sogard is earmarked for the strong side of a 3B platoon, making him most useful in NL-only formats.

Fisher has had severe problems making contact at the big-league level, whiffing in a whopping 36.5% of his trips to the plate to date, and things didn't seem to go much better in a late-season audition following his trade to the Blue Jays. Barring a change in his approach during spring training, he'll be a low-batting average, counting numbers type an AL-only team should only consider to round out its roster.

Prior to 2019, Dickerson last played in 2016, teasing a fantasy-friendly power-speed combination with good plate skills. Back surgery in 2017 followed by Tommy John surgery in 2018 kept Dickerson off the diamond, even for rehab. The Padres assigned the 29-year old outfielder to Triple-A El Paso where slashed .360/.462/.593, earning a 2019 promotion in early May. He played sparingly before spending time on the IL with a sore wrist. Dickerson was then dealt to the Giants, where he slashed an impressive .386/.449.773, facing mainly right-handers before being shelved due to an oblique issue. After returning, Dickerson couldn't find his stroke, compiling just a .164/.219/.209 line down the stretch. The Giants saw enough to bring Dickerson back in 2020. His injury history will keep the cost minimal, just be ready for the inevitable IL visits.

Bohm tore through three competitive levels of the minor leagues in what was his first full season as a pro in 2019, slashing .305/.378/.518 with 21 home runs in 125 games combined between Class A Lakewood, Class A Clearwater and Double-A Reading, enjoying success at each. While there's some question about his long-term position, he might begin 2020 as high as the Triple-A level, meaning that continued progress might earn him an in-season promotion. It's best to assume his ETA is 2021 and that he's more of a dynasty league prospect, but NL-only redraft managers can find worse players to stash.

After a year in Arlington, Pence is returning to the Giants where he spent six-plus years. Aided by a reworked swing, the 2019 ball, and a huge upgrade to a very favorable hitting venue, Pence posted the best slash line of his career .297/.358/.553, albeit in just half a season. He even swiped six bags in seven tries -- not bad for a 36-year old veteran still running with 85th-percentile sprint speed. That said, Pence once again was felled by the injury bug. Pence could win a corner outfield spot, or he could bounce around, backing up three lefty-swinging starters. Returning to Oracle Park should dampen Pence's production, though he'll play enough to be rostered in NL-only formats.

On the surface, Almora Jr.'s average exit velocity didn't change last season. Upon closer inspection, his average exit velocity on fly balls increased 3 mph, while his ground ball and line drive components dropped. The result was a spike in power but a precipitous drop in line drive and ground ball hits since only 28% of Almora's contact was classified as a fly ball. If Almora didn't have such a long track record of a low fly ball percentage, he'd be a candidate for continued power growth. As is, he's a middling outfielder, best suited for NL-only play, since he's yet to eclipse 480 plate appearances, averaging 388 a season over the past three campaigns.

Following an eye-opening 2018 campaign, Wendle was expected to have a key role in Tampa Bay's lineup last season. Instead, the 29-year-old was hampered by a string of injuries that resulted in three trips to the IL and limited him to 263 plate appearances. When he did play, Wendle looked nothing like the .300 hitter from his breakout campaign. He finished the season with a .231 average and .275 wOBA while posting the lowest walk rate (5.3%) of his career. It's fair to assume that the injuries played a part in his struggles, and Wendle should get some leeway after posting solid averages throughout his professional career. Still, he no longer projects to be an everyday player and adds very little in the power department. He could be in play for fantasy managers in desperate need of steals but otherwise figures to be a fixture on the waiver wire.

After taking a big step forward offensively in 2018, Hedges not only fell back, but he landed well worse than in 2017, his first as a regular. He improved his hard-hit rate, but it was still just 18th-percentile. Hedges lofted more batted balls, but since they were weakly hit, they resulted in outs. This was particularly true in Petco Park where Hedges' numbers were worse than on the road. The 27-year-old receiver remains one of the best behind the dish, setting a new personal best with 22 defensive runs saved. Despite the fine glovework, Hedges will likely lose playing time to Francisco Mejia, placing him in a reserve role where he'll have no fantasy value whatsoever.

Elevating more batted balls doesn't work for everyone. In some cases, it can be a detriment, as fly balls staying in the yard result in fewer hits than ground balls. In 2019, Barnes increased his fly ball rate from 26% to 42%, but his average exit velocity on fly balls dropped from 89.8 mph to 88.4 mph, while his average fly ball distance fell from 326.9 feet to 303.5 feet. In addition, Barnes' plate skills took a step back, as he whiffed more and walked less, costing him his starting job and resulting in a visit to the farm. Barnes is slated to back up Will Smith, but unless he reverts to old form or refines his current approach, he's not relevant in any fantasy format.

Rojas, who coupled good speed with decent pop as a member of the Astros' farm system, got a late-2019 audition with the Diamondbacks, where his previous reputation for contact simply eroded. He also hit too many balls on the ground, meaning there are adjustments to make before he'd be more than an NL-only flier. Rojas should compete for a utility role this spring, but seems a long shot to grab a significant number of plate appearances.

The Marlins signed Ramirez to a minor-league deal and assigned him to Triple-A New Orleans to open the season. The 2018 Double-A batting champion was slashing .355/.408/.591 when he received the call to report to South Beach. Ramirez compiled a respectable .276/.312/.416 slash in his rookie campaign, playing nearly every day in the outfield. A 14.5% HR/FB rate is above league average, but a 23% flyball rate limited Ramirez's ability to tap into that power. However, 92nd percentile spring speed along with a 57% groundball rate helped prop up a .328 batting average on balls in play. Unfortunately, Ramirez didn't take full advantage of his speed, stealing only two bases. After the Marlins brought in a few veterans, it appears Ramirez is ticketed for a reserve role, though an injury to any one of several players could return Ramirez to the starting lineup.

When Cleveland acquired Bauers from Tampa Bay prior to the 2019 season, the expectation was that the 26.8 K% he registered in his rookie campaign would drift closer to the mid-teens mark he had posted throughout his minor league career. Instead, the left-hander's strikeout rate actually increased to 27.2% last season. That's not good for a hitter who has displayed only moderate power (.163 career ISO) and who doesn't awe observers with any specific skill. Bauers does possess some speed -- he stole 20 bases in the minors in 2017 -- but he has thus far proved to be a detriment on the basepaths at the major league level, getting thrown out in half of his 18 theft attempts. His best offensive asset is his ability to draw a walk (career 12.2 BB%), but that's unlikely to earn him a full-time role unless he fixes his contact issues and better taps into his raw power.

While injuries cost Astudillo two months of 2019 and his power stroke dipped, he showed the same kind of elite, unusual-for-this-era contact in 58 Twins games that he had everywhere else during his professional career. His 95.8% contact rate in the majors represented the ninth consecutive pro campaign in which that number was 95%-plus, giving him a batting average floor that makes him a wise No. 2 catcher -- he's still eligible there -- if you opt to go the cheap route at the position. But beware: he lacks upside in any other facet of his game.

It seems like Cervelli's career concussions are catching up to his career homers, as the veteran catcher was sidelined with the malady again last season. However, doctors deemed it safe for Cervelli to continue squatting behind the dish. He began the season with the Pirates before getting concussed in May. Many thought Cervelli would retire after getting let go in August, but Cervelli and the Braves had other plans. The 33-year-old receiver finished the season with Atlanta but was released after the playoffs. Cervelli signed with the Marlins, with whom he'll back up Jorge Alfaro. Coming off a .213/.302/.348 season, there are better fantasy options, not even considering his health risk.

Arcia posted some of the best counting stats of his career last season, but he had an otherwise miserable campaign at the plate, finishing last among qualified hitters in wRC+. Despite the struggles, the Brewers still decided to bring him back for another season rather than not tender him a contract. He won't have the shortstop spot all to himself like he did in the past, as the Brewers acquired Luis Urias from the Padres in an effort to get more offense at the position. Urias could miss the start of the season due to a hand injury, so Arcia could still find himself in the lineup come Opening Day. However, everyday at-bats could be hard to come by when both are healthy, and Arcia will likely need that in order to be of much help for fantasy players.

Frazier had a golden opportunity to lock down a regular spot in the Yankees' outfield in what was an injury-plagued season for their roster, and while he slashed .324/.342/.632 in an 18 game audition following Giancarlo Stanton's loss to the IL, injuries sidetracked the rookie himself thereafter. An ankle issue cost Frazier 11 games, he struck out 43 times in his next 123 at-bats and was returned to Triple-A Scranton/Wilkes-Barre, where he remained for all but a September call-up in a reserve role. We've now been waiting three seasons for this top prospect to flourish, and his walk and hard-contact drops in 2019 were troubling. Frazier finds himself in a similar spot entering 2020, with a trade perhaps his best chance at a breakthrough opportunity, so regard him as a stash only.

A strong camp resulted in Hamilton cracking the Royals' Opening Day lineup, batting ninth as the so-called second leadoff hitter. The speedster stole eight bases in April despite a paltry .298 OBP, but things went downhill from there, as nagging injuries and poor on-base skills led to the Royals releasing Hamilton in mid-August after hitting an anemic .211/.275/.269 and stealing 17 bags in 22 tries. The Braves claimed Hamilton and used him sparingly down the stretch, though he did improve his decimals to .268/.375/.317 with Atlanta and stole another four bases. Now 29 years old, it is apparent Hamilton isn't going to get on base enough to pile up stolen bases. He will likely be relegated to late-inning defensive duties and pinch running the rest of his career.

Despite swatting 49 homers from 2017-18, Healy was earmarked to be a bench piece for the Mariners heading into the 2019 campaign. However, a spring injury to Kyle Seager opened the hot corner for Healy. He was pacing towards a season similar to the previous campaign before a hip issue in late May ended up costing Healy the rest of the season. Healy's 21% strikeout rate is palatable in today's landscape, but he doesn't hit the ball hard enough to support a 44% fly ball rate, resulting in too many cans of corn. Signing with the Brewers and playing in Miller Park could help, but even at a thinner-than-usual corner infield position, Healy is an afterthought in mixed formats.

After averaging 117 games and 391 plate appearances for the Nationals over the previous four seasons, Taylor appeared in only 53 contests with 97 trips to the dish last season, spending half the summer toiling for Double-A Hartford. Taylor's numbers weren't far from his career levels, but they weren't good enough for the eventual World Series champions. Taylor's 46% ground ball approach is good for a player with 92nd percentile spring speed, but he fails to supplement it, sporting a 7% walk rate and a strikeout rate consistently north of 30%. After looking like he could develop into a fourth outfielder, Taylor's career path is headed towards late-inning defensive replacement and pinch-runner, neither of which are helpful for your fantasy roster.

After enjoying a rejuvenated 2018 campaign, Kemp opened 2019 with the Reds but failed to recapture the magic, slashing just .200/.210/.283 in 20 games before being shelved with a bruised rib after crashing into the outfield wall. Cincinnati let Kemp go before he was fully healthy. The veteran outfielder caught on with the Mets but was released before playing a game. Once he recovered, Kemp worked out on his own, signing a minor-league deal with the Marlins where he'll try to break camp as a reserve. Entering his age-35 season, Kemp is a longshot to make the bigs, let alone be fantasy relevant.

Still just 25 years old, McKinney is poised to embark on his eighth professional season after breaking into rookie ball as a teenager. Back then, he exhibited plate skills beyond his 18 years, but as he progressed, he's been unable to maintain them, let alone develop in other areas. Last season, McKinney broke camp with the Blue Jays but was shuttled to Triple-A Buffalo three times before ending the season in Toronto. Contact and walks were once his calling card, but last season, he fanned at a 26.4% clip while walking just 6.9% of the time. The Blue Jays are assembling a formidable offense. If McKinney wants to be a part, he'll need to ratchet up his on-base skills.

Duggar was playing regularly before visiting the IL in mid-June with a sore back. When healthy, he was assigned to Triple-A Sacramento before being recalled again in early August. Duggar was back for only a week when he hurt his shoulder diving in the outfield. Surgery wasn't necessary, but the injury shut Duggar down for the season. He is expected to be ready for spring training. On the field, Duggar posted a 64 wRC+, the 14th-lowest among non-catchers with at least 250 plate appearances. Add in his 1-for-5 record in stealing bases and Duggar was one of the worst fantasy performers in the sport. Duggar's prospects aren't much better for the upcoming season. His strikeout rate is high while his quality of contact is poor. There's nothing to see here in all but the deepest of formats.

The White Sox gave Engel plenty of chances to impress during their rebuild, but he failed to take advantage, posting an 84 wRC+ last season. To be fair, during the previous two seasons, he recorded 69 and 39 marks, so he was trending in the right direction. Still, with the South Siders upgrading their offense, Engel's chance for significant playing time has waned. In particular, Engel's 31% career strikeout rate and 5% walk rate are both poor, relegating him to reserve outfielder status, if he makes the team at all.

After a huge 2018 in the minors, Kirilloff disappointed in his first taste of Double-A ball last season, though the wrist issues that plagued him for most of the first half probably contributed to that. He slashed .283/.343/.413, but finished on a high note, batting .319/.371/.496 with five homers over his final 28 games. Kirilloff will probably begin the year at Triple-A, and if he continues to excel at making contact with his line-drive stroke, he might see some time in Minnesota by midseason. He's one of the better dynasty-league prospects and warrants a stash in deep-mixed/AL-only leagues.

Initially considered a glove-first shortstop, Cozart worked at his offense, peaking with a 139 wRC+ with the Reds in 2017. However, injuries and aging instigated a sharp decline, as Cozart posted an anemic .124/.178/.144 line in 38 games for the Angels last season before succumbing to a shoulder injury that required season-ending surgery. The Halos packaged Cozart and prospect Will Wilson to the Giants to get out from under Cozart's contract, but San Francisco released the 34-year-old shortstop. The addition of a 26th roster spot could help Cozart land a job. However, there aren't ample enough fantasy roster spots to include Cozart.

Once a highly-acclaimed Yankees prospect, Fowler hasn't looked the same since rupturing his patella in June 2017 in his only MLB appearance in pinstripes. The Athletics acquired Fowler as part of the Sonny Gray deal, but he was quickly passed up by Ramon Laureano on the depth chart. Fowler spent the entire 2019 season on the farm, hitting .277/.333/.477 for Triple-A Las Vegas and swiping a dozen bags. Las Vegas is one of the best hitting venues in the minors and Triple-A used the same ball as the majors, though, so Fowler's production wasn't enough to warrant a promotion to The Show. Oakland continues carrying a deep roster, which has Fowler ticketed for another season riding buses, hoping to rekindle the promise he exhibited in the lower minors.

There's a fall from grace,and then there's Schebler. In 2017, Schebler blasted 30 homers for the Reds. Last season, he was slashing .123/.253/.222 before Cincinnati sent him to Triple-A Louisville where he posted a .216/.274/.325 line. There's a saying stating once you display a skill, you own it. The thing is, once you display lack of a skill, you own that too. Schebler's skills are poor across the board: high strikeouts, a low average exit velocity, and a huge groundball tilt all dampen power. Maybe he will rediscover his stroke, but it's not worth investing any draft capital to find out.

Markakis continues to chug along as one of baseball's most steady, yet unspectacular, performers. Over the past three seasons, his .286 BA and .415 SLG were nearly identical to his career marks, and advanced metrics suggest little change from his days in Baltimore. Markakis was slowed by a fractured wrist last season but still put up a .300 xBA while registering his typical low strikeout rate (12.6%) and high walk rate (10.0%). The 14-year veteran also ranked above the 80th percentile in both average exit velocity (91.2 mph) and hard-hit rate (41.0%), though he launched only nine home runs due to a meager 27.1% fly ball rate and 7.3 degree average launch angle. Therein lies the rub with Markakis -- for all his useful contact and on-base skills, it has been a while since he produced enough in the counting stats to be more than a fringe fantasy asset. Expect more of the same in 2020.
Mancini is being treated for colon cancer and is not expected to play in 2020.

Posey missed time in 2019 with a hamstring injury, as well as a concussion, and had arguably the worst performance of his career at the plate. Behind the plate, Posey is still an excellent receiver, which guarantees him extra playing time and the ability to provide more production than the average catcher when on the field. A healthy Posey contributes to batting average and good run production for the catching position, but we have not seen the complete version of him since 2017. The declining exit velocity and increasing groundball rate provide little reason to believe there is a bounce-back season on the way. He was once a lock as a top-10 catcher, but even taking him in the top 15 in 2020 feels like a reach, given his lack of upside.

In 2019, Desmond's ground ball rate dropped significantly to 47%, but that's still too high to take advantage of Coors Field -- not just for power but also for hits. Further, Desmond's sprint speed was just 65th percentile, down from 89th in 2016. Losing a couple of steps didn't affect Desmond's infield hits, as a jump in softly hit grounders made it easier to beat more out. But after averaging 20 steals over the previous nine seasons, Desmond attempted only six in 2019, with just three successful tries. As he enters his age-34 season, a return to previous levels seems highly unlikely. Although he has two years left on his contract, Desmond's lack of power and speed and the emergence of some young talent could send him to the bench more than usual. Even so, playing in Coors Field makes him viable, especially in leagues that allow for daily lineup moves.
